1
00:02:19,950 --> 00:02:22,317
- What's new?
- Same old daily bunkeroo.

2
00:02:22,420 --> 00:02:26,414
Mr. Powers says he wants to see
that foreign stuff as soon as it comes in.

3
00:02:29,995 --> 00:02:32,260
Don't declare war for a few minutes.

4
00:02:47,184 --> 00:02:50,416
"According to a high official,
it is believed"...

5
00:02:50,956 --> 00:02:52,821
Foreign correspondent.

6
00:02:53,358 --> 00:02:56,726
I could get more news out of Europe
looking in the crystal ball.

7
00:02:56,796 --> 00:02:59,663
That Stebbins cable has a morsel in it.

8
00:02:59,967 --> 00:03:02,959
Stebbins makes me sick.
They all make me sick.

9
00:03:03,671 --> 00:03:04,899
Europe about to blow up...

10
00:03:04,973 --> 00:03:08,967
and all I can get from my foreign staff
is a daily guessing game.

11
00:03:09,779 --> 00:03:12,839
- I want some facts, Mr. Bradley.
- For instance?

12
00:03:13,216 --> 00:03:14,649
Any kind of fact.

13
00:03:15,085 --> 00:03:17,145
There must be something
going on in Europe...

14
00:03:17,221 --> 00:03:18,985
beside a nervous breakdown.

15
00:03:19,323 --> 00:03:22,054
Why not try sending me over, Mr. Powers?

16
00:03:23,730 --> 00:03:26,460
You've written a book
on economics or something.

17
00:03:26,533 --> 00:03:28,558
<i>The Twilight of Feudalism?</i>

18
00:03:28,636 --> 00:03:31,434
- Yes. It was very well received.
- Not by me.

19
00:03:31,505 --> 00:03:35,670
I don't want any more economists, sages,
or oracles bombinating over our cable.

20
00:03:35,744 --> 00:03:37,007
I want a reporter.

21
00:03:37,079 --> 00:03:40,379
Someone who doesn't know the difference
between an ism and a kangaroo.

22
00:03:40,450 --> 00:03:43,715
<i>A good, honest crime reporter.
That's what the Globe needs.</i>

23
00:03:43,787 --> 00:03:45,221
That's what Europe needs.

24
00:03:45,290 --> 00:03:48,260
There's a crime hatching
on that bedeviled continent.

25
00:03:48,726 --> 00:03:50,217
Wait a minute.

26
00:03:51,030 --> 00:03:53,727
I've got something
that might pass for an idea.

27
00:03:56,003 --> 00:03:59,200
Who was that fellow that ran down
the payroll robbery last week?

28
00:03:59,273 --> 00:04:00,605
You mean Johnny Jones.

29
00:04:00,676 --> 00:04:03,406
He beat up a policeman, didn't he,
in the line of duty?

30
00:04:03,478 --> 00:04:06,505
Yes. There's some talk at the city desk
of firing him.

31
00:04:07,350 --> 00:04:09,080
Beat up a policeman?

32
00:04:10,020 --> 00:04:11,988
Sounds ideal for Europe.

33
00:04:14,125 --> 00:04:16,390
Send Mr. Jones up here right away.

34
00:04:17,262 --> 00:04:20,323
- Mr. Powers wants to see you, Mr. Jones.
- He does?

35
00:04:20,399 --> 00:04:23,233
- You should come to his office right away.
- What about?

36
00:04:23,303 --> 00:04:25,238
I ain't in his confidence.

37
00:04:25,306 --> 00:04:28,139
Tell him to save his breath.
Tell him I've resigned.

38
00:04:28,209 --> 00:04:32,374
- I'm supposed to bring you there.
- Okay. Wait till I open this.

39
00:04:36,921 --> 00:04:40,186
Where's Mr. Jones?
I told you to send him right up here!

40
00:04:45,965 --> 00:04:47,626
- Are you Mr. Jones?
- Yes.

41
00:04:47,900 --> 00:04:49,299
Sit down, please.

42
00:04:51,505 --> 00:04:53,940
- You mind a personal question?
- No.

43
00:04:54,141 --> 00:04:56,042
- Are you married?
- No luck.

44
00:04:56,112 --> 00:04:57,305
Single?

45
00:04:58,414 --> 00:05:00,382
- Ever been in Europe?
- No.

46
00:05:02,319 --> 00:05:05,379
What's your opinion
of the present European crisis, Mr. Jones?

47
00:05:05,456 --> 00:05:06,855
What crisis?

48
00:05:09,028 --> 00:05:11,553
I'm referring to
the impending war, Mr. Jones.

49
00:05:11,630 --> 00:05:15,727
That. To tell you the truth,
I haven't given it much thought.

50
00:05:16,102 --> 00:05:18,627
You don't keep up
with our foreign news, do you?

51
00:05:18,706 --> 00:05:22,142
If you're gonna fire me,
you can scrap the intelligence test.

52
00:05:22,210 --> 00:05:23,700
It's perfectly okay with me.

53
00:05:23,779 --> 00:05:26,908
I can get a job on any newspaper in town
within an hour. So long.

54
00:05:26,983 --> 00:05:29,315
Wait a minute. Nobody fired you.

55
00:05:29,719 --> 00:05:32,780
How would you like to cover
the biggest story in the world today?

56
00:05:32,856 --> 00:05:34,824
With an expense account,
I'll cover anything.

57
00:05:34,892 --> 00:05:36,417
You'll get an expense account.

58
00:05:36,494 --> 00:05:38,793
- Okay, what's the story?
- Europe.

59
00:05:38,963 --> 00:05:41,865
I'm afraid I'm not exactly equipped,
but I could read up.

60
00:05:41,934 --> 00:05:44,870
No reading up. I like you just as you are.

61
00:05:44,971 --> 00:05:47,770
What Europe needs
is a fresh, unused mind.

62
00:05:47,942 --> 00:05:50,604
- Foreign correspondent?
- No. Reporter.

63
00:05:52,347 --> 00:05:55,943
I don't want correspondence. I want news.

64
00:05:56,853 --> 00:06:00,220
- Can you dig up some news in Europe?
- I'll be happy to try, sir.

65
00:06:00,291 --> 00:06:01,553
This is what I mean:

66
00:06:01,625 --> 00:06:04,823
Mr. Van Meer, when questioned
by our oracle, Mr. Stebbins...

67
00:06:04,895 --> 00:06:06,797
refused to open his mouth.

68
00:06:06,866 --> 00:06:08,857
A 1,200-word cable told...

69
00:06:08,935 --> 00:06:11,803
to the fact that
the great Van Meer had nothing to say.

70
00:06:11,871 --> 00:06:15,741
Know what that's doing? It's driving
our readers crazy with frustration.

71
00:06:15,810 --> 00:06:19,678
- Who's Van Meer?
- Keynote to the European situation today.

72
00:06:19,982 --> 00:06:23,315
If Van Meer stays
at the helm of his country's affairs...

73
00:06:23,385 --> 00:06:26,253
for the next three months,
it may mean peace in Europe.

74
00:06:26,323 --> 00:06:29,521
If we knew what he was thinking
we'd know where Europe stands.

75
00:06:29,594 --> 00:06:31,994
- German?
- No. Holland's strongman.

76
00:06:32,197 --> 00:06:34,961
One of the two signers
of the Dutch treaty with Belgium.

77
00:06:35,033 --> 00:06:38,663
Now, this is your first assignment.
I want you to talk with him...

78
00:06:38,738 --> 00:06:42,038
find out what's in that treaty,
and what he thinks will happen. Facts.

79
00:06:42,376 --> 00:06:44,106
- Van Meer?
- Right.

80
00:06:44,179 --> 00:06:45,544
- Anybody else?
- No.

81
00:06:45,647 --> 00:06:48,276
How about Hitler?
Don't you think we should pump him?

82
00:06:48,350 --> 00:06:50,512
He must have something on his mind.

83
00:06:53,757 --> 00:06:56,692
<i>- Yes?
- Mr. Stephen Fisher to see you.</i>

84
00:06:57,095 --> 00:06:58,653
Tell him to come in.

85
00:06:58,730 --> 00:07:00,357
Ever hear of Stephen Fisher?

86
00:07:00,431 --> 00:07:03,128
- I'm afraid he's not on my beat.
- He is from now on.

87
00:07:03,202 --> 00:07:06,400
He's head of the Universal Peace Party
and very close to Van Meer.

88
00:07:06,473 --> 00:07:09,704
They're both working
to prevent Europe going up in flames.

89
00:07:10,778 --> 00:07:14,374
How do you do, Mr. Fisher?
Nice of you to come over.

90
00:07:14,616 --> 00:07:16,140
- Sit down.
- Thank you.

91
00:07:16,218 --> 00:07:18,949
Mr. Fisher, Mr. Jones,
our new foreign correspondent.

92
00:07:19,022 --> 00:07:20,250
I want you to know each other.

93
00:07:20,323 --> 00:07:21,881
How do you do, Mr. Jones.

94
00:07:21,959 --> 00:07:26,123
Jones. I don't like that name.
It's going to handicap you, young man.

95
00:07:26,731 --> 00:07:30,634
Now, wait a minute.
I've got some sort of a name here.

96
00:07:32,071 --> 00:07:34,632
Yes. Haverstock. Huntley Haverstock.

97
00:07:34,708 --> 00:07:36,972
Sounds more important,
doesn't it, Mr. Fisher?

98
00:07:37,044 --> 00:07:38,569
Yes, very dashing.

99
00:07:38,646 --> 00:07:40,637
Sounds better than Richard Harding Davis.

100
00:07:40,716 --> 00:07:43,275
- What's the matter with that?
- We can't use that.

101
00:07:43,352 --> 00:07:46,948
That's the name of one of our
greatest war correspondents 40 years ago.

102
00:07:47,023 --> 00:07:50,926
Speak up, young man. You don't mind
being Huntley Haverstock, do you?

103
00:07:50,995 --> 00:07:52,622
A rose by any name, sir.

104
00:07:52,698 --> 00:07:56,498
It's exciting being present at the
christening of a newspaper correspondent.

105
00:07:56,568 --> 00:07:58,833
Shouldnt we break
a bottle of champagne?

106
00:07:58,905 --> 00:08:03,002
Break one over my head to see
if I'm still awake. Huntley Haverstock.

107
00:08:03,376 --> 00:08:06,745
Mr. Haverstock, you better get started.
You've got a lot to do.

108
00:08:06,815 --> 00:08:08,806
- Passports, photos, visas...
- Expenses.

109
00:08:08,884 --> 00:08:10,511
I'll send a note to the cashier.

110
00:08:10,585 --> 00:08:14,522
- I hope you brought your Sunday articles.
- I managed three of them.

111
00:08:14,590 --> 00:08:17,719
- See you in London then, Mr. Haverstock.
- Yes, of course.

112
00:08:17,794 --> 00:08:20,821
Thank you, Mr. Powers.
Thank you for everything.

113
00:08:20,899 --> 00:08:23,198
Except Huntley Haverstock.

114
00:08:40,623 --> 00:08:44,184
Get a load of this, Mother.
How's it look? Chic?

115
00:08:44,695 --> 00:08:47,790
Don't wear it over one eye.
It makes you look like a dandy.

116
00:08:47,865 --> 00:08:50,835
You always think the boys are wearing
their hats over one eye.

117
00:08:50,902 --> 00:08:54,361
- Let him wear it the way it is.
- He'll have to wear a stovepipe in London.

118
00:08:54,440 --> 00:08:56,931
- They call them poppers over there.
- Toppers.

119
00:08:57,010 --> 00:09:00,138
Bobby, put that in the box for Uncle John,
will you?

120
00:09:00,213 --> 00:09:02,739
- Let me try it on.
- No, I want to try it on.

121
00:09:02,817 --> 00:09:05,719
- Now he's a regular war correspondent.
- Without a war.

122
00:09:05,788 --> 00:09:07,484
I'm afraid he'll get his war.

123
00:09:07,556 --> 00:09:10,924
- They're throwing a big bluff over there.
- Let's hope so.

124
00:09:11,661 --> 00:09:14,426
How do you like the way
we've our little nest furnished?

125
00:09:14,498 --> 00:09:18,492
If I were you, I'd hang lighter curtains,
and move that sofa out here.

126
00:09:18,570 --> 00:09:20,801
It's too bad you haven't an open fireplace.

127
00:09:20,873 --> 00:09:24,207
If you'd speak to the captain,
I think he'd attend to everything.

128
00:09:24,278 --> 00:09:27,042
All ashore that's going ashore!

129
00:09:30,819 --> 00:09:32,309
Now, Mother.

130
00:09:33,689 --> 00:09:35,055
Goodbye, John.

131
00:09:35,124 --> 00:09:37,218
- Take care of yourself.
- Thank you.

132
00:10:09,300 --> 00:10:11,860
<i>You're Jones?
I'm Stebbins, London man for the Globe.</i>

133
00:10:11,936 --> 00:10:14,871
Mr. Powers told me you'd probably
be here. Nice of you to come.

134
00:10:14,940 --> 00:10:16,908
Reminds me. I lost mine on the way over.

135
00:10:16,976 --> 00:10:20,208
I can say your other name, too.
That Huntley...

136
00:10:21,281 --> 00:10:22,749
I could say it yesterday...

137
00:10:22,817 --> 00:10:25,810
but I had a rather tough session
with the boys last night.

138
00:10:25,887 --> 00:10:29,153
- So I'll stick to Jones if you don't mind.
- Jones is great with me.

139
00:10:29,224 --> 00:10:32,956
Let's go. This crowd's making me nervous.
My nerves aren't in the pink.

140
00:10:33,029 --> 00:10:35,760
Just take it easy.
I'll follow you right along.

141
00:10:35,833 --> 00:10:39,565
Porter, bring those bags. And don't
bang them into my knees from behind.

142
00:10:42,942 --> 00:10:45,433
What about a drink
after that long train ride?

143
00:10:45,511 --> 00:10:47,377
Sounds like a very logical idea.

144
00:10:47,448 --> 00:10:50,077
I may not act it,
but I've been here 25 years.

145
00:10:50,151 --> 00:10:53,484
<i>London man for the Globe
and they haven't caught onto me yet.</i>

146
00:10:53,555 --> 00:10:54,886
How'd you manage it?

147
00:10:54,956 --> 00:10:57,425
Cable back the government handouts
and sign them...

148
00:10:57,493 --> 00:10:58,983
"Our London correspondent."

149
00:10:59,062 --> 00:11:01,223
- What's yours?
- Scotch and soda, please.

150
00:11:01,298 --> 00:11:02,765
Miss?

151
00:11:05,703 --> 00:11:07,000
Miss, please.

152
00:11:08,039 --> 00:11:11,703
- Scotch and soda, and a glass of milk.
- A glass of milk?

153
00:11:11,978 --> 00:11:15,778
I'm on the wagon. I went to the doctor
today about these jitters I got...

154
00:11:15,849 --> 00:11:19,844
and he said it was the wagon for a month
or a whole new set of organs.

155
00:11:19,920 --> 00:11:22,321
I can't afford a whole new set of organs.

156
00:11:22,390 --> 00:11:25,725
If I'd known you're on the wagon,
I could have got along without this.

157
00:11:25,795 --> 00:11:27,889
But as long as it's here...

158
00:11:28,465 --> 00:11:29,796
Good luck.

159
00:11:31,870 --> 00:11:32,996
Good?

160
00:11:33,505 --> 00:11:37,636
- Yeah, just like any other Scotch and soda.
- That's what I thought.

161
00:11:39,078 --> 00:11:42,674
Doesrt taste the way it did
when I was a baby. That's got poison in it.

162
00:11:42,749 --> 00:11:45,014
Speaking of that, I've got some pills
I got to take.

163
00:11:45,086 --> 00:11:48,021
Here's some cables that have been
coming over from New York.

164
00:11:48,090 --> 00:11:52,117
They love to cable. It makes them think
you're working for them.

165
00:11:52,194 --> 00:11:55,687
There's an invitation to that lunch
for the Dutchman Van Meer tomorrow.

166
00:11:55,765 --> 00:11:57,199
I guess that's your dish.

167
00:11:57,268 --> 00:12:01,069
This is given by the Universal Peace Party.
That's Fisher's organization, right?

168
00:12:01,139 --> 00:12:03,733
I don't know.
I don't follow those things very much.

169
00:12:03,808 --> 00:12:07,871
New York wants it, I send it.
That's the secret of being a correspondent.

170
00:12:07,948 --> 00:12:09,848
Been doing it 25 years.

171
00:12:10,884 --> 00:12:13,375
Twenty-five years, and I end up on milk.

172
00:12:36,750 --> 00:12:38,615
Good morning. How's the water wagon?

173
00:12:38,686 --> 00:12:41,484
Look at that.
One of them shook off this morning.

174
00:12:43,225 --> 00:12:46,251
I'm just on my way
to the Van Meer luncheon.

175
00:12:46,329 --> 00:12:49,766
I'm lunching with old man Clark.
He's the International Press...

176
00:12:49,833 --> 00:12:53,963
Here you are. I didn't know whether
to meet you in the grill or upstairs.

177
00:12:54,505 --> 00:12:57,805
Goodbye, Stebbins. Goodbye, Miss Clark.

178
00:12:58,376 --> 00:13:01,346
Who's he calling Clark? He's got his nerve.

179
00:13:01,480 --> 00:13:03,676
Some fresh American reporter.

180
00:13:04,150 --> 00:13:05,947
Good morning, Mr. Van Meer.

181
00:13:09,858 --> 00:13:13,454
I beg your pardon, sir.
You are Mr. Van Meer, aren't you?

182
00:13:13,562 --> 00:13:14,996
That's my name, yes.

183
00:13:15,064 --> 00:13:17,555
I'm Haverstock. You don't know me.
I'm an American.

184
00:13:17,634 --> 00:13:20,604
And I just happen to be
on my way to your luncheon.

185
00:13:20,671 --> 00:13:23,106
- Then, perhaps...
- That's very kind of you, sir...

186
00:13:23,173 --> 00:13:26,008
Come, come. It's all in a good cause.

187
00:13:27,412 --> 00:13:28,812
Savoy Hotel.

188
00:13:34,955 --> 00:13:38,619
- This is very kind of you.
- It's a pleasure, my boy.

189
00:13:38,693 --> 00:13:40,889
I dislike riding alone.

190
00:13:41,130 --> 00:13:43,655
One thinks too much while riding alone.

191
00:13:43,732 --> 00:13:47,534
Yes, exactly. The Polish situation,
and the Dutch treaty with the Belgians...

192
00:13:47,605 --> 00:13:50,005
must be on your mind
quite a lot these days.

193
00:13:50,074 --> 00:13:52,908
What do you feel
that England will do in case the Nazis...

194
00:13:52,978 --> 00:13:54,946
England is so beautiful.

195
00:13:55,648 --> 00:13:58,674
It's nice to see London in the sunshine.

196
00:13:59,185 --> 00:14:02,884
Always there's lots of rain or fog.

197
00:14:03,124 --> 00:14:04,853
Also it is August.

198
00:14:04,926 --> 00:14:07,690
I found out it was August.
That's pretty good for me.

199
00:14:07,762 --> 00:14:09,424
Would you mind telling me...

200
00:14:09,498 --> 00:14:12,263
how you feel about Mr. Fisher
and his Peace Organization?

201
00:14:12,335 --> 00:14:14,531
You know Mr. Fisher?

202
00:14:14,604 --> 00:14:18,234
A very fine man. And a good man.

203
00:14:18,310 --> 00:14:21,973
I wish there were more like him
in the world just now.

204
00:14:22,048 --> 00:14:24,949
I take it you don't think
there's much hope for peace?

205
00:14:25,017 --> 00:14:28,146
I mean, you don't think
one little peace organization...

206
00:14:28,221 --> 00:14:30,817
can make much headway
against the European war panic?

207
00:14:30,892 --> 00:14:33,086
I would like to think so.

208
00:14:33,160 --> 00:14:34,891
Look at those birds.

209
00:14:34,964 --> 00:14:38,866
No matter how big the city,
there must always be parks...

210
00:14:39,068 --> 00:14:41,503
and places for the birds to live.

211
00:14:41,972 --> 00:14:44,566
I was walking
through the park this morning...

212
00:14:44,642 --> 00:14:47,577
and I saw several people feeding the birds.

213
00:14:47,846 --> 00:14:51,716
It's a good sign at a time like this.
Is it not?

214
00:14:51,785 --> 00:14:53,115
Yes, it's a dandy sign...

215
00:14:53,186 --> 00:14:56,247
but I do think that right now
birds are the least of our problems.

216
00:14:56,323 --> 00:14:59,555
Your country, for instance.
What's its attitude toward these matters?

217
00:14:59,627 --> 00:15:01,926
We're now near the Savoy.

218
00:15:06,369 --> 00:15:09,498
- How much?
- A shilling.

219
00:15:11,142 --> 00:15:12,541
That's fine.

220
00:15:17,849 --> 00:15:21,981
By the way, young man,
what newspaper do you represent?

221
00:15:23,023 --> 00:15:25,753
As a matter of fact,
I'm not exactly a reporter...

222
00:15:25,826 --> 00:15:28,990
but I was trying to get you to talk.
I didn't want bird talk either.

223
00:15:29,064 --> 00:15:30,690
I gathered that.

224
00:15:31,834 --> 00:15:35,737
Just what was it
that you were trying to get me to tell you?

225
00:15:35,806 --> 00:15:40,141
I'm trying to find out what you know
about the possibility of a general war.

226
00:15:40,211 --> 00:15:42,009
How do you really feel about it?

227
00:15:42,080 --> 00:15:45,482
My boy, I feel very old and sad...

228
00:15:46,786 --> 00:15:48,253
and helpless.

229
00:16:01,705 --> 00:16:03,195
I did have one.

230
00:16:37,415 --> 00:16:40,249
The last news from Poland
was very alarming.

231
00:16:40,318 --> 00:16:43,153
- Nobody wants a war...
- Then we don't have to have it.

232
00:16:43,223 --> 00:16:46,522
You must understand, often circumstances
over which we've no control...

233
00:16:46,593 --> 00:16:50,189
Yes, those convenient circumstances
over which we have no control.

234
00:16:50,266 --> 00:16:52,496
It's always odd,
but they usually bring on a war.

235
00:16:52,568 --> 00:16:55,435
You never hear of circumstances
over which we've no control...

236
00:16:55,504 --> 00:16:57,666
rushing us into peace, do you?

237
00:16:57,741 --> 00:16:59,572
Very determined woman, my daughter.

238
00:16:59,644 --> 00:17:03,080
Come on. Let's go and see
if you can pick a fight somewhere else.

239
00:17:03,147 --> 00:17:04,945
- Good for you.
- Wasrt he a bore?

240
00:17:05,017 --> 00:17:07,111
Many won'thy people are, bless them.

241
00:17:07,186 --> 00:17:09,518
How do you like to be fishing in Ireland
right now?

242
00:17:09,589 --> 00:17:12,251
We haven't had a good sail
or swim together in months.

243
00:17:12,325 --> 00:17:15,022
Not even a game of cribbage. Miss them?

244
00:17:15,296 --> 00:17:17,060
There's the Admiral.

245
00:17:17,232 --> 00:17:19,962
He has a weakness for you.
Go on. Do your stuff.

246
00:17:20,068 --> 00:17:23,630
Here you are. The Jones that became
a Haverstock. Have a good trip?

247
00:17:23,706 --> 00:17:25,538
Still wish you were Richard Harding Davis.

248
00:17:25,609 --> 00:17:28,476
- So do I, sir. Anything except...
- Hello.

249
00:17:28,545 --> 00:17:33,041
<i>Mrs. Appleby, meet Huntley Haverstock,
Special Correspondent, New York Globe.</i>

250
00:17:33,118 --> 00:17:35,643
- Foreign correspondent? Not really.
- Cross my heart.

251
00:17:35,722 --> 00:17:39,488
You look such a dear, sweet boy.
You don't seem a bit like the others.

252
00:17:39,559 --> 00:17:41,551
But I'm sure you're marvelous at it.

253
00:17:41,628 --> 00:17:44,029
Do you know a friend of mine,
Monte Rockingham?

254
00:17:44,098 --> 00:17:47,364
He's in the embassy at Istanbul.
Or is it Honolulu?

255
00:17:47,903 --> 00:17:50,737
Do help me with this
distinguished-looking gentleman here.

256
00:17:50,807 --> 00:17:54,710
I can't make any headway with him,
but I'm sure he speaks some language.

257
00:17:54,778 --> 00:17:56,746
I haven't the least idea who he is...

258
00:17:56,814 --> 00:18:00,013
but there's nobody here
who isn't internationally important.

259
00:18:00,086 --> 00:18:02,316
- This is Mr. Haver...
- Stock.

260
00:18:09,062 --> 00:18:10,428
No English?

261
00:18:13,368 --> 00:18:14,563
Try German.

262
00:18:15,804 --> 00:18:18,205
Splendid. What else do you know?

263
00:18:18,274 --> 00:18:20,640
- Only pig Latin.
- Pig Latin.

264
00:18:20,710 --> 00:18:23,305
Here we are. This will do it.

265
00:18:26,952 --> 00:18:29,513
Now we're getting somewhere.
The universal language.

266
00:18:29,588 --> 00:18:31,147
Dear Maharajah.

267
00:18:42,905 --> 00:18:44,896
Well, they come in pairs.

268
00:18:45,141 --> 00:18:48,009
If you speak English,
give me a hand with the laughing Latvian.

269
00:18:48,078 --> 00:18:50,570
- What's his racket? What's he talking?
- Latvian.

270
00:18:50,648 --> 00:18:53,242
No kidding. I didn't know
the Lats had a language.

271
00:18:53,317 --> 00:18:55,717
I thought they just rubbed noses.

272
00:18:57,222 --> 00:19:01,319
- You mean you actually speak Latvian?
- Just enough to get about.

273
00:19:01,594 --> 00:19:04,587
What does just enough to get about
consist of in Latvian?

274
00:19:04,665 --> 00:19:06,600
I don't think you'd have any trouble.

275
00:19:06,667 --> 00:19:09,137
Be a comfort to know when I get to Latvia.

276
00:19:09,204 --> 00:19:12,003
You think there's a chance
of you getting to Latvia soon?

277
00:19:12,075 --> 00:19:13,565
Never can tell in my racket.

278
00:19:13,644 --> 00:19:16,112
I suppose you've guessed
I'm a foreign correspondent.

279
00:19:16,179 --> 00:19:17,977
Are you? That's nice.

280
00:19:19,017 --> 00:19:22,544
I see you're taking notes.
Are you covering this affair, too?

281
00:19:22,620 --> 00:19:24,248
I sort of work here.

282
00:19:24,322 --> 00:19:27,088
Publicity? You're just the one
I'm looking for.

283
00:19:27,160 --> 00:19:29,993
We've got to go in a secret conference
right away.

284
00:19:34,135 --> 00:19:35,966
Me? Excuse me.

285
00:19:36,705 --> 00:19:39,469
I beg your pardon, sir.
I have a Latvian friend here...

286
00:19:39,541 --> 00:19:42,272
who's particularly interested
in the origin of the kilt.

287
00:19:42,346 --> 00:19:46,009
I wonder if you'd be interested
in talking to him. He's a lovely fellow.

288
00:19:46,084 --> 00:19:48,245
It's a most amazing story.

289
00:19:48,687 --> 00:19:52,714
You see, the Greeks, in the early period,
they used to wear a kilt.

290
00:19:53,226 --> 00:19:55,957
Now, what is this big secret conference
all about?

291
00:19:56,029 --> 00:20:00,660
It's no secret as far as I'm concerned.
However, I'll let you in on that later.

292
00:20:00,735 --> 00:20:04,933
Since you're handling publicity here,
give me a line on what it's about...

293
00:20:05,006 --> 00:20:06,975
this league for peace and understanding.

294
00:20:07,042 --> 00:20:08,977
Just what is it you'd like to know?

295
00:20:09,045 --> 00:20:12,310
In the first place, is this Mr. Fisher
entirely on the level?

296
00:20:12,382 --> 00:20:13,872
Very much so.

297
00:20:14,118 --> 00:20:17,349
- Seems like a very nice guy.
- He is, I assure you.

298
00:20:17,623 --> 00:20:21,720
What is it that makes him or you
think that an organization like this...

299
00:20:21,795 --> 00:20:23,660
made up of well-meaning amateurs...

300
00:20:23,730 --> 00:20:26,131
buck up against those
tough military boys of Europe?

301
00:20:26,200 --> 00:20:30,797
It's the well-meaning amateurs
who do the fighting when the war comes.

302
00:20:30,872 --> 00:20:33,865
- Luncheon is served.
- Please don't go yet.

303
00:20:33,943 --> 00:20:36,139
You don't want those
dreary chicken patties.

304
00:20:36,213 --> 00:20:37,736
I'm sorry. I must go.

305
00:20:37,815 --> 00:20:40,079
Then sit at the press table with me.

306
00:20:40,150 --> 00:20:43,143
Nobody ever listens to the speeches,
and we could talk.

307
00:20:43,221 --> 00:20:44,950
You don't even know my name yet.

308
00:20:45,023 --> 00:20:47,254
- Is it necessary?
- It is to me.

309
00:20:47,326 --> 00:20:49,852
Don't mind if you hear
it's Huntley Haverstock...

310
00:20:49,929 --> 00:20:51,864
because it's really Jones.

311
00:20:51,932 --> 00:20:54,527
- What's yours?
- Mine's really Smith.

312
00:20:54,902 --> 00:20:57,769
Don't mind if you hear it's anything else.

313
00:21:02,979 --> 00:21:04,640
- Waiter?
- Yes, sir.

314
00:21:05,748 --> 00:21:07,740
Same young lady. Try again.

315
00:21:07,818 --> 00:21:11,618
I've taken the young lady 13 notes, sir.
She won't accept any more.

316
00:21:15,995 --> 00:21:19,864
Milords, ladies and gentlemen...

317
00:21:20,969 --> 00:21:23,062
pray silence for your chairman...

318
00:21:24,038 --> 00:21:25,801
Mr. Stephen Fisher.

319
00:21:28,577 --> 00:21:31,239
Ladies and gentlemen,
I have an announcement to make...

320
00:21:31,313 --> 00:21:33,805
which I'm sure will be
a great disappointment to us all.

321
00:21:33,885 --> 00:21:36,547
I've just received this telegram
from Mr. Van Meer...

322
00:21:36,621 --> 00:21:39,647
who was to have been
our guest of honor today.

323
00:21:39,891 --> 00:21:43,693
"Deeply regret. Called away suddenly
owing to unforeseen circumstances.

324
00:21:43,763 --> 00:21:46,664
"And I will be unable
to attend your meeting as planned.

325
00:21:46,733 --> 00:21:49,259
"I am with you and your work
with all my heart.

326
00:21:49,337 --> 00:21:52,363
"I could not have said more
had I been there."

327
00:21:53,642 --> 00:21:56,703
Although this removes
one of our star attractions...

328
00:21:56,779 --> 00:22:00,011
we may, as a result, have more time
to tell you from the inside...

329
00:22:00,083 --> 00:22:04,214
just what this party has stood for
and why we've asked you here today.

330
00:22:04,555 --> 00:22:07,047
I can think of no one
more competent to do this...

331
00:22:07,125 --> 00:22:09,253
than the speaker I'm about to introduce.

332
00:22:09,328 --> 00:22:11,853
I trust you won't think this a family affair...

333
00:22:11,932 --> 00:22:16,029
when I say that I refer to my daughter
Miss Carol Fisher.

334
00:22:24,113 --> 00:22:27,174
Milords, ladies and gentlemen...

335
00:22:28,085 --> 00:22:30,576
pray silence for Miss Carol Fisher.

336
00:22:40,634 --> 00:22:42,262
Ladies and gentlemen...

337
00:22:42,336 --> 00:22:46,103
I trust, even making allowances
for a father's exuberance...

338
00:22:46,408 --> 00:22:49,434
you do not think I'm in any way
being put forward today...

339
00:22:49,511 --> 00:22:51,911
as a substitute for Mr. Van Meer.

340
00:22:52,115 --> 00:22:55,573
Unappily for us,
no one can take Mr. Van Meer's place.

341
00:22:56,386 --> 00:22:59,687
What I can do possibly
is to clear up a few misapprehensions...

342
00:22:59,758 --> 00:23:02,818
that have crept into
the public discussion of this movement...

343
00:23:02,894 --> 00:23:06,262
and revise some of the epithets
that have been applied to us...

344
00:23:06,366 --> 00:23:09,530
by some who have not gone
as deeply into the matter as they might.

345
00:23:09,603 --> 00:23:12,436
The female of the species
is deadlier than the male.

346
00:23:12,507 --> 00:23:15,203
...as a group of well-meaning amateurs.

347
00:23:15,410 --> 00:23:18,744
Now, I'm sure there's some of you
here today who think of us as such.

348
00:23:18,814 --> 00:23:22,979
I'd like to ask anyone who has called us
well-meaning amateurs...

349
00:23:23,053 --> 00:23:27,081
to stand up and tell me
just why a well-meaning amateur...

350
00:23:27,158 --> 00:23:30,890
is any less reliable than a well-meaning
professional at a moment like this.

351
00:23:30,963 --> 00:23:32,590
But I'll not take the time.

352
00:23:32,664 --> 00:23:35,793
The world's been run long enough
by the well-meaning professional.

353
00:23:35,869 --> 00:23:38,464
We might give the amateurs
a chance now.

354
00:23:38,538 --> 00:23:42,306
But what I really want to do
is to give you a very brief idea of...

355
00:23:46,049 --> 00:23:49,213
just how far-reaching
our amateur plans are.

356
00:23:53,057 --> 00:23:54,422
Use your notes.

357
00:23:55,060 --> 00:23:56,652
And just...

358
00:23:57,863 --> 00:23:59,694
why we ask for your support...

359
00:23:59,765 --> 00:24:01,392
professional or amateur.

360
00:24:02,903 --> 00:24:06,168
What I mean to say is that,
however much one may...

361
00:24:09,844 --> 00:24:11,642
I mean, we should both...

362
00:24:13,550 --> 00:24:15,074
Both of us...

363
00:25:39,322 --> 00:25:41,450
Tell them to wait in there.

364
00:25:42,526 --> 00:25:45,655
- Mr. Fisher, how are you?
- When did you get over here?

365
00:25:45,730 --> 00:25:48,995
Just now. I had a cable.
This conference is my first assignment.

366
00:25:49,067 --> 00:25:53,004
An ironic assignment. A peace conference
under the shadow of war.

367
00:25:53,072 --> 00:25:54,199
It's really coming?

368
00:25:54,273 --> 00:25:56,675
Today and tomorrow will tell.
There's still hope.

369
00:25:56,743 --> 00:25:58,211
I'm going back to London today.

370
00:25:58,279 --> 00:26:02,080
Leaving for London? I just got here.
But the conference is just beginning.

371
00:26:02,151 --> 00:26:05,952
Today and tomorrow the work for peace
is in London rather than Amsterdam.

372
00:26:06,022 --> 00:26:09,789
You're taking your whole staff
back to London with you, including your...

373
00:26:09,860 --> 00:26:13,296
No. I have someone staying here
who'll give you all the help you need.

374
00:26:13,364 --> 00:26:16,198
You'll be in very good hands. Here she is.

375
00:26:17,169 --> 00:26:18,728
Mrs. Appleby. Mr. Haverstock.

376
00:26:18,805 --> 00:26:21,934
We met at the luncheon.
You remember him, don't you.

377
00:26:22,009 --> 00:26:24,409
He's nice, but I still can't understand him.

378
00:26:24,478 --> 00:26:27,744
<i>Dr. Williamson, this is Huntley Haverstock
of the New York Globe.</i>

379
00:26:27,816 --> 00:26:30,307
He's unfamiliar with Amsterdam
and peace meetings.

380
00:26:30,386 --> 00:26:32,911
Would you be good enough
to take him under your wing?

381
00:26:32,989 --> 00:26:35,982
Perhaps you'll both see
that he samples Dutch cheese...

382
00:26:36,059 --> 00:26:37,459
at dinner tonight.

383
00:26:37,528 --> 00:26:41,863
Now I must see what unlucky person
will give up his seat on the London plane.

384
00:26:41,933 --> 00:26:44,232
Don't get into any mischief, will you?

385
00:26:44,770 --> 00:26:45,965
Mischief?

386
00:26:46,039 --> 00:26:48,098
- Your first visit to Amsterdam?
- Yes.

387
00:26:48,174 --> 00:26:50,803
You must let me take you
to Rembrandt's house...

388
00:26:50,878 --> 00:26:55,145
It might be a good idea if we went over
the agenda of the conference with him.

389
00:26:55,217 --> 00:26:57,778
If you'll excuse me. I think I see a friend.

390
00:27:09,401 --> 00:27:11,494
Mr. Van Meer. How are you?

391
00:27:11,937 --> 00:27:14,963
We somehow seemed to lose each other
day before yesterday.

392
00:27:15,041 --> 00:27:17,306
I'm so sorry you were called away.

393
00:27:17,944 --> 00:27:19,469
Don't you remember me?

394
00:27:19,546 --> 00:27:23,006
We shared the same cab together
on the way to the luncheon.

395
00:27:23,384 --> 00:27:24,409
Excuse me.

396
00:27:24,485 --> 00:27:27,284
May I have your picture, Mr. Van Meer?
Thank you.

397
00:27:41,207 --> 00:27:42,698
There he goes!

398
00:27:48,917 --> 00:27:50,612
He's getting away!

399
00:28:38,311 --> 00:28:40,245
Follow that car, quick!

400
00:28:46,788 --> 00:28:48,951
You'd better get out of here.
Might be dangerous.

401
00:28:49,025 --> 00:28:50,788
Don't be silly. Drive on.

402
00:28:53,097 --> 00:28:55,190
- Who has he shot?
- Van Meer assassinated.

403
00:28:55,266 --> 00:28:56,928
- Dead?
- Looked like it.

404
00:28:57,002 --> 00:29:00,165
- Bad show.
- Couldrt be worse from his viewpoint.

405
00:29:03,810 --> 00:29:06,439
Do you mind shoving your knees
out of the way.

406
00:29:26,604 --> 00:29:29,073
- You better hop in the back, old girl.
- Hurry.

407
00:29:37,519 --> 00:29:39,452
Safety glass. I wonder whose make.

408
00:29:39,520 --> 00:29:41,546
- Good chauffeur you've got.
- Yes, isn't he?

409
00:29:41,623 --> 00:29:42,955
You know each other?

410
00:29:43,025 --> 00:29:47,463
This is Scott ffolliott, newspaperman,
same as you. Foreign correspondent.

411
00:29:47,531 --> 00:29:49,830
- Mr. Haverstock, Mr. Ffolliott.
- With a double "F."

412
00:29:49,901 --> 00:29:51,562
How do you do?

413
00:29:51,668 --> 00:29:53,000
I don't get the double "F."

414
00:29:53,071 --> 00:29:55,164
They're at the beginning. Both small "F's".

415
00:29:55,240 --> 00:29:56,765
They can't be at the beginning.

416
00:29:56,842 --> 00:29:59,403
One of my ancestors
was beheaded by Henry Vlll.

417
00:29:59,478 --> 00:30:02,745
His wife dropped the capital letter
to commemorate it. There it is.

418
00:30:04,919 --> 00:30:08,617
- How do you say it, like a stutter?
- Just a straight "fuh."

419
00:30:28,881 --> 00:30:32,216
- It's stopped raining. Surs coming up.
- The police are coming.

420
00:30:59,153 --> 00:31:02,282
It's the most amazing disappearing trick
I've ever seen.

421
00:31:06,062 --> 00:31:09,225
You don't suppose they could've got up
that high, do you?

422
00:31:22,582 --> 00:31:23,571
Vanished.

423
00:31:26,087 --> 00:31:30,081
- Take a look for yourself.
- Tell him your name with the small "F"s.

424
00:31:30,158 --> 00:31:31,854
That'll be a bit over his head.

425
00:31:37,034 --> 00:31:39,298
This isn't catching any assassins.

426
00:31:39,370 --> 00:31:41,635
We should have kept a policeman
and played bridge.

427
00:31:41,706 --> 00:31:43,229
I guess you're right.

428
00:31:48,614 --> 00:31:50,845
I'll bet 2-to-1 on the derby.

429
00:32:16,382 --> 00:32:18,350
Look at those sails on that windmill.

430
00:32:18,418 --> 00:32:21,719
You'll get used to those
when you've been in Holland longer.

431
00:32:22,690 --> 00:32:25,286
I was sure they were going
against the wind.

432
00:32:25,360 --> 00:32:27,794
Why don't you lie down on the grass
and cool off?

433
00:32:27,863 --> 00:32:31,231
I'll cool off in due time.
But first get the police back here.

434
00:32:31,301 --> 00:32:33,496
- The police again?
- We don't want them.

435
00:32:33,570 --> 00:32:35,504
- I won't be prosecuting.
- No...

436
00:32:35,573 --> 00:32:37,838
- Get the police, our mars there.
- Where?

437
00:32:37,910 --> 00:32:40,105
- In that mill.
- What makes you think so?

438
00:32:40,179 --> 00:32:43,479
A lot of things can happen
while I'm explaining. Please get the police.

439
00:32:43,550 --> 00:32:45,211
I'd go myself if I spoke the language.

440
00:32:45,285 --> 00:32:47,447
- What will you do?
- A little bit of snooping.

441
00:32:47,521 --> 00:32:49,648
I hate to seem executive.
But this is serious.

442
00:32:49,725 --> 00:32:52,853
- Come on, Scott.
- All right. You shall have your police.

443
00:33:20,194 --> 00:33:23,358
It's a signal.
It's a signal for that plane to land.

444
00:36:03,398 --> 00:36:06,834
Come in and close the door, mister.

445
00:36:09,137 --> 00:36:12,267
Why, Mr. Van Meer. It isn't possible.

446
00:36:14,411 --> 00:36:16,846
I've just been given a drug.

447
00:36:17,715 --> 00:36:19,479
Drug of some sort.

448
00:36:19,818 --> 00:36:23,755
But I saw you shot just outside
the conference hall. I saw it!

449
00:36:24,358 --> 00:36:26,189
They gave it to me...

450
00:36:26,626 --> 00:36:28,753
when they moved me from...

451
00:36:30,131 --> 00:36:32,258
It's beginning now.

452
00:36:32,567 --> 00:36:34,934
But the man I saw shot was a dead image.

453
00:36:35,004 --> 00:36:38,532
The man you saw shot, it wasrt me.

454
00:36:39,676 --> 00:36:41,268
He was a...

455
00:36:42,012 --> 00:36:45,244
substitute that looked like me.

456
00:36:45,316 --> 00:36:46,750
But why? What...

457
00:36:46,818 --> 00:36:50,380
They want the world to think...

458
00:36:51,224 --> 00:36:54,922
that I've been assassinated. Yes.

459
00:36:55,963 --> 00:36:58,023
To conceal the fact...

460
00:36:59,067 --> 00:37:03,095
- that I'm in their hands.
- Their hands? Who are they?

461
00:37:05,107 --> 00:37:07,042
I can't explain.

462
00:37:07,744 --> 00:37:09,645
I'm not certain.

463
00:37:11,082 --> 00:37:14,746
This drug. I can hardly think.

464
00:37:17,823 --> 00:37:19,792
All that I can tell you...

465
00:37:19,859 --> 00:37:23,488
is that they are going
to take me away by plane...

466
00:37:25,132 --> 00:37:26,566
like a bird.

467
00:37:27,836 --> 00:37:30,532
Always there are places in the city...

468
00:37:31,340 --> 00:37:34,309
where birds can get crumbs.

469
00:37:37,415 --> 00:37:38,745
Birds.

470
00:37:40,652 --> 00:37:41,915
Quick.

471
00:37:43,656 --> 00:37:45,021
A pencil.

472
00:37:45,157 --> 00:37:46,988
Give me the pen.

473
00:41:32,273 --> 00:41:34,400
See? Old mill.

474
00:41:35,510 --> 00:41:36,944
Up the road.

475
00:41:38,247 --> 00:41:39,373
Look.

476
00:41:40,383 --> 00:41:41,441
Man.

477
00:41:43,019 --> 00:41:44,851
Old mill. Understand?

478
00:41:45,790 --> 00:41:49,750
- Does anyone here speak English?
- We speak English in the school.

479
00:41:49,827 --> 00:41:51,922
Why have you been holding out on me?

480
00:41:51,997 --> 00:41:54,831
Look, tell these two policemen
to come with me.

481
00:41:54,901 --> 00:41:58,360
Very, very important.
Big old prisoner. Old mill.

482
00:41:58,572 --> 00:42:01,040
Tell them to follow me.
Do you understand?

483
00:42:15,927 --> 00:42:18,555
Yeah. That's what
I've been trying to tell you. Come on.

484
00:42:40,157 --> 00:42:41,624
They've gone.

485
00:42:54,742 --> 00:42:56,471
They've killed him.

486
00:43:03,987 --> 00:43:05,546
But it isn't...

487
00:43:05,655 --> 00:43:07,089
Who are you?

488
00:43:08,493 --> 00:43:10,291
Where are the others?

489
00:43:16,369 --> 00:43:19,270
There's been a frame-up.
Ask him where the others have gone.

490
00:43:26,415 --> 00:43:29,714
He doesn't know what you're
talking about. There are no other people.

491
00:43:29,785 --> 00:43:31,913
And in any case,
he's been asleep here all day.

492
00:43:31,988 --> 00:43:34,856
He's lying. I talked to Van Meer
in this very room.

493
00:43:43,469 --> 00:43:47,031
There's one thing I can show you.
The assassins' car. The one we followed.

494
00:43:55,083 --> 00:43:58,781
Rather a unique specimen, old boy.
The only one horsepower car in the world.

495
00:43:58,856 --> 00:44:01,017
I don't care what you say.
That car was here.

496
00:44:01,091 --> 00:44:04,994
Listen, I know I look a fool,
but there's something fishy going on.

497
00:44:05,063 --> 00:44:07,759
There's a big story in this.
I can smell it, I can feel it.

498
00:44:07,832 --> 00:44:10,428
I'll get to the bottom of it,
if it's the last thing I do.

499
00:44:10,503 --> 00:44:12,665
Nothing's going to stop me.
Do you understand?

500
00:44:12,739 --> 00:44:16,836
I'll prove that that wasrt Van Meer
that was assassinated, but his double.

501
00:44:37,235 --> 00:44:38,533
Who is it?

502
00:44:41,908 --> 00:44:43,672
All right. Come in.

503
00:44:49,752 --> 00:44:51,913
- Mr. Haverstock?
- Yes.

504
00:44:52,289 --> 00:44:54,883
What are you, the house detective?
You werert announced.

505
00:44:54,958 --> 00:44:58,451
- I'm sorry, sir. We asked at the desk.
- Policemen?

506
00:44:58,529 --> 00:45:00,964
You're not here
to apologize about the windmill?

507
00:45:01,033 --> 00:45:05,333
We simply want you to come with us
and tell your story to our chief of police.

508
00:45:05,404 --> 00:45:08,806
Does this chief of police speak English,
because I'm a very busy man.

509
00:45:08,875 --> 00:45:12,438
It will take no more than half an hour.
We all speak English.

510
00:45:12,513 --> 00:45:15,506
That's marvelous. That's more
than I can say for my country.

511
00:45:15,584 --> 00:45:18,213
Would you sit down?
I have to make a phone call.

512
00:45:18,287 --> 00:45:20,187
Dinner date with a young lady.

513
00:45:35,709 --> 00:45:38,611
The exchange doesn't answer.
I'll call later.

514
00:45:38,979 --> 00:45:40,880
Look, I'm a very quick bather.

515
00:45:40,949 --> 00:45:44,510
Would you excuse me while I
jump in the tub and have a quick shave?

516
00:45:44,586 --> 00:45:47,054
Look at some magazines. I'll be right back.

517
00:45:47,122 --> 00:45:49,456
You can't you bring
the chief of police here?

518
00:45:49,527 --> 00:45:52,256
- No, I am afraid not.
- I thought not.

519
00:47:04,386 --> 00:47:05,716
Please don't bother to come.

520
00:47:05,787 --> 00:47:08,383
You'll find it on my dressing table.

521
00:47:24,945 --> 00:47:27,277
- We meet again.
- So it seems.

522
00:47:28,048 --> 00:47:30,779
Quite a lot's happened
since I last saw you.

523
00:47:30,851 --> 00:47:32,150
So I see.

524
00:47:33,189 --> 00:47:36,990
I had quite a chase
after that guy outside Amsterdam.

525
00:47:37,126 --> 00:47:40,290
It's quite a country.
It's interesting. Windmills and tulips.

526
00:47:40,363 --> 00:47:42,264
Did you find everything you...

527
00:47:44,302 --> 00:47:48,035
We were just talking about the tulips.
Don't seem to be any.

528
00:47:48,207 --> 00:47:50,802
I really think I should be going now.

529
00:47:51,845 --> 00:47:54,337
Thank you very much for the powder.

530
00:47:54,515 --> 00:47:56,347
Must you really go now?

531
00:47:56,417 --> 00:47:59,080
Yes, I must be going now. Really.

532
00:48:02,858 --> 00:48:04,087
Goodbye.

533
00:48:10,601 --> 00:48:12,797
You've made quite a day of it,
haven't you?

534
00:48:12,871 --> 00:48:16,171
Making fools of Scott ffolliott and me,
breaking into my bedroom...

535
00:48:16,242 --> 00:48:18,609
and disgracing me
before a friend of my father's.

536
00:48:18,678 --> 00:48:21,773
What are your plans now?
You might at least have clothes on.

537
00:48:21,849 --> 00:48:24,374
Take it easy. This is serious.
I've got to talk to you.

538
00:48:24,453 --> 00:48:27,320
I've seen your serious business.
What're you doing here?

539
00:48:27,389 --> 00:48:29,186
- I'm escaping.
- Escaping from what?

540
00:48:29,258 --> 00:48:31,249
From some fellows
in my room about to kill me.

541
00:48:31,326 --> 00:48:32,555
May I ask who?

542
00:48:32,629 --> 00:48:35,793
Two gentlemen disguised as policemen,
waiting to take me for a ride.

543
00:48:35,866 --> 00:48:39,394
- You're talking through your hat.
- I'm not talking through my hat.

544
00:48:39,470 --> 00:48:42,566
I've thrown a monkey wrench
into some international dirty business.

545
00:48:42,642 --> 00:48:45,133
I know Van Meer's alive.
That's why want to kill me.

546
00:48:45,211 --> 00:48:46,577
I can think of others.

547
00:48:46,647 --> 00:48:48,808
You've got to help me.
Not for my sake alone...

548
00:48:48,882 --> 00:48:50,509
but it's the biggest story in Europe.

549
00:48:50,584 --> 00:48:54,522
Your childish mind is out of place
in Europe as you are in my bedroom.

550
00:48:55,557 --> 00:48:57,081
Get over there.

551
00:49:14,614 --> 00:49:16,081
You see what you're doing?

552
00:49:16,149 --> 00:49:19,483
All this is going back to London
and will be common gossip by tomorrow.

553
00:49:19,553 --> 00:49:22,523
I don't care for myself,
but my father's engaged in great work.

554
00:49:22,590 --> 00:49:24,456
He's trying to help avert a dreadful war...

555
00:49:24,527 --> 00:49:27,088
and this is just the sort of thing
to discredit him.

556
00:49:27,163 --> 00:49:28,859
I know you care nothing about our work.

557
00:49:28,932 --> 00:49:32,129
All you're interested in is having fun
with windmills and bathrooms.

558
00:49:32,202 --> 00:49:33,864
You don't believe I'm in trouble?

559
00:49:33,938 --> 00:49:36,100
You'll be in lot of trouble
if you don't get out.

560
00:49:36,175 --> 00:49:38,575
Now for the last time, please go.

561
00:49:42,983 --> 00:49:46,886
Okay. But I want you to know exactly
what's going to happen when I do go.

562
00:49:46,954 --> 00:49:49,981
I'll go back to my room
and try and shake those fellows off...

563
00:49:50,058 --> 00:49:51,252
but I won't succeed.

564
00:49:51,326 --> 00:49:54,490
They'll stick to me like a
couple of tattoo marks until they get me.

565
00:49:54,564 --> 00:49:58,524
They'll stop at nothing. I seem to know
too much. And you're right.

566
00:49:58,602 --> 00:50:01,071
I don't know much about
your crackpot peace movement...

567
00:50:01,139 --> 00:50:04,541
I don't know what's wrong with Europe.
But I know a story when I see one.

568
00:50:04,610 --> 00:50:08,103
I'll keep after it until either I get it
or it gets me.

569
00:50:08,248 --> 00:50:11,218
Sorry you have those
derogatory opinions of me...

570
00:50:11,284 --> 00:50:13,378
but I guess that can't be helped.

571
00:50:14,655 --> 00:50:17,648
So long. It's been nice knowing you.

572
00:50:21,931 --> 00:50:23,455
I said goodbye.

573
00:50:30,008 --> 00:50:31,270
Don't go.

574
00:50:34,514 --> 00:50:37,779
I guess I could have handled those fellows
with a little luck.

575
00:50:37,850 --> 00:50:40,411
We mustrt take any chances.
We should get help.

576
00:50:40,487 --> 00:50:42,012
That's what I had in mind.

577
00:50:42,090 --> 00:50:45,958
- I'll get Dr. Williamson...
- Wait. They might not understand.

578
00:50:47,096 --> 00:50:48,893
They have understood.

579
00:50:55,706 --> 00:50:58,800
We could catch the night boat to England
if we could get out.

580
00:50:58,877 --> 00:51:01,937
That's the hitch.
What's that friend's name, that "ff"?

581
00:51:02,015 --> 00:51:04,882
- Ffolliott.
- Get me Mr. Ffolliott's room, please.

582
00:51:05,718 --> 00:51:07,050
Left the hotel?

583
00:51:07,121 --> 00:51:09,555
That's strange.
We were to dine together tonight.

584
00:51:09,623 --> 00:51:13,458
- He realized how much I meant to you.
- You'd mean more with your clothes on.

585
00:51:13,528 --> 00:51:14,825
You like the intellectual type.

586
00:51:14,896 --> 00:51:16,728
- Say, I've got an idea.
- What?

587
00:51:16,799 --> 00:51:19,394
Give me the manager, please.
Buzz for the valet.

588
00:51:19,470 --> 00:51:23,236
Is this the manager?
This is Mr. Haverstock in 537.

589
00:51:23,307 --> 00:51:25,071
What kind of hotel is this?

590
00:51:25,143 --> 00:51:28,113
My bathtub leaks, phone's out of order,
and I've been robbed.

591
00:51:28,180 --> 00:51:31,275
Will you send somebody up right away?
Thank you.

592
00:51:32,519 --> 00:51:35,454
Operator, send a waiter up to 537.

593
00:51:35,523 --> 00:51:38,287
And ask the chambermaid
to bring up some clean sheets.

594
00:51:38,359 --> 00:51:39,657
I've set mine on fire.

595
00:51:39,728 --> 00:51:41,821
And I'd like my windows cleaned.

596
00:51:41,897 --> 00:51:45,994
And ask boots to come get my shoes.
Hurry up. That's a good girl.

597
00:51:46,069 --> 00:51:49,130
Clutter up that room nicely
for those two guys.

598
00:51:49,640 --> 00:51:51,699
It's the valet. Come in.

599
00:51:52,477 --> 00:51:54,206
- Do you speak English?
- Yes, sir.

600
00:51:54,279 --> 00:51:56,372
Go to my room, 537...

601
00:51:56,448 --> 00:51:59,544
and get me shirt, tie, suit, and a hat.

602
00:52:01,522 --> 00:52:04,515
You see, my husband's
waiting in the room for this gentleman.

603
00:53:26,126 --> 00:53:29,619
No sign of them yet.
Let's hide ourselves in the cabin.

604
00:53:36,072 --> 00:53:38,598
- Full up, sir. Sorry.
- Not even a small cabin?

605
00:53:38,676 --> 00:53:41,406
Not a thing.
Everybody in a hurry to get home.

606
00:53:41,479 --> 00:53:44,540
I have a rather rare banknote
you might be interested in.

607
00:53:44,616 --> 00:53:47,450
It's a memento,
that is if you collect rare banknotes.

608
00:53:47,520 --> 00:53:51,286
It's no use, sir. I'd do it if I could,
but there just isn't a place left.

609
00:53:51,357 --> 00:53:55,056
On English ships, you come up against
such an air of incorruptibility.

610
00:53:55,130 --> 00:53:58,362
As a matter of fact,
I've just had a cabin returned.

611
00:53:58,434 --> 00:54:00,163
Can I have your name, sir?

612
00:54:00,870 --> 00:54:04,136
One cabin isn't going to do us much good.
We just can't...

613
00:54:04,207 --> 00:54:07,541
I fully intended to sleep in the lounge.
I hope you didn't think I...

614
00:54:07,612 --> 00:54:10,410
No, of course not. It's very kind of you.

615
00:54:10,982 --> 00:54:12,211
I'll take it.

616
00:54:12,284 --> 00:54:14,809
I'm sorry, sir. I'm afraid it's too late now.

617
00:54:14,887 --> 00:54:19,019
You had some doubt about taking it,
so I had to let that gentleman have it.

618
00:54:19,093 --> 00:54:22,256
That's too bad. It's such a rare £5 note.

619
00:54:22,330 --> 00:54:25,323
The water mark's upside down.
I think you'd have loved it.

620
00:54:25,400 --> 00:54:27,368
Well, perhaps next time.

621
00:55:08,087 --> 00:55:11,181
- Were you really going to tip that man £5?
- Of course.

622
00:55:11,257 --> 00:55:13,624
I charge all my traveling expenses
to the office.

623
00:55:13,694 --> 00:55:15,457
Corrupting an official, £5.

624
00:55:15,529 --> 00:55:18,226
You're just a wee bit unscrupulous,
aren't you?

625
00:55:18,299 --> 00:55:20,598
Not unscrupulous. Just in love.

626
00:55:21,003 --> 00:55:24,461
- It's the same thing, I suppose.
- I beg your pardon?

627
00:55:24,940 --> 00:55:26,374
I beg yours.

628
00:55:26,910 --> 00:55:29,937
You see, I love you,
and I want to marry you.

629
00:55:33,218 --> 00:55:35,778
I love you, and I want to marry you.

630
00:55:36,822 --> 00:55:40,259
That cuts our love scene down
quite a bit, doesn't it?

631
00:55:40,326 --> 00:55:43,421
- Do you mind?
- Not at all. It's made a new man of me.

632
00:55:43,498 --> 00:55:45,192
I hope not entirely new.

633
00:55:45,266 --> 00:55:48,726
It took me some time
to get used to the first man you were.

634
00:55:48,804 --> 00:55:52,206
To be perfectly frank with you,
I expected a little more argument.

635
00:55:52,275 --> 00:55:55,302
I'm really left with quite a few things
I very much wanted to say.

636
00:55:55,379 --> 00:55:58,816
Save them until after we're married.
I imagine they'll sound better then.

637
00:55:58,883 --> 00:56:01,044
I've saved things to say then, too.

638
00:56:01,119 --> 00:56:03,611
You were really quite sure of yourself,
werert you?

639
00:56:03,689 --> 00:56:07,126
I didn't think I had a chance.
A guy's got a right to dream, hasn't he?

640
00:56:07,194 --> 00:56:08,422
Evidently.

641
00:56:09,063 --> 00:56:11,293
Do you think your father will understand?

642
00:56:11,365 --> 00:56:14,096
I think that Father
will be delighted, frankly.

643
00:56:34,089 --> 00:56:35,648
All right, sir.

644
00:56:44,001 --> 00:56:47,028
- Good morning, Miss Carol.
- Stiles, this is Mr. Haverstock.

645
00:56:47,105 --> 00:56:49,666
- Is Father up yet?
- Yes, miss. He's having breakfast.

646
00:56:49,741 --> 00:56:50,902
Come on.

647
00:56:56,650 --> 00:56:59,677
- Hello, Father.
- What on earth are you doing in London?

648
00:56:59,753 --> 00:57:02,188
Mr. Haverstock brought me back
on the boat.

649
00:57:02,258 --> 00:57:05,989
- You're not ill? You look healthy.
- I'm fine. It's Mr. Haverstock.

650
00:57:06,063 --> 00:57:07,996
I hope you don't mind my barging in.

651
00:57:08,065 --> 00:57:09,965
On the contrary, I'm delighted to see you.

652
00:57:10,033 --> 00:57:13,595
You cover a lot of territory, don't you?
You didn't even wire me.

653
00:57:13,671 --> 00:57:16,038
For that I hope
your trip was uncomfortable.

654
00:57:16,108 --> 00:57:17,336
It wasrt so bad.

655
00:57:17,409 --> 00:57:21,506
The boat was crowded, we couldn't get
any cabins, but we slept on the deck.

656
00:57:21,581 --> 00:57:23,742
<i>Monsieur Krug, how nice to see you again.</i>

657
00:57:23,818 --> 00:57:26,685
<i>But you haven't met
Mr. Haverstock, Monsieur Krug.</i>

658
00:57:28,556 --> 00:57:31,152
<i>Monsieur Krug is a member
of the Baruvian embassy staff.</i>

659
00:57:31,227 --> 00:57:33,559
Sit down, Haverstock. Have breakfast.

660
00:57:33,630 --> 00:57:36,463
I should tidy up, but I'm simply starved.

661
00:57:40,672 --> 00:57:43,301
So you were in Amsterdam
yesterday, Mr. Haverstock.

662
00:57:43,376 --> 00:57:46,106
Poor Van Meer.
His death is a personal loss.

663
00:57:46,179 --> 00:57:48,114
Of all people, why Van Meer?

664
00:57:48,181 --> 00:57:51,549
You can't ask why with assassins.
There's no logic in killing.

665
00:57:51,618 --> 00:57:54,554
We can't spare such men
in a world like ours.

666
00:57:54,956 --> 00:57:57,550
Did you by any chance
meet him, Mr. Haverstock?

667
00:57:57,626 --> 00:58:01,324
- Not formally, but I saw him die.
- Horrible.

668
00:58:02,365 --> 00:58:06,302
As a matter of fact, I chased the man
that shot him, and almost caught him.

669
00:58:06,370 --> 00:58:08,771
Mr. Haverstock is a newspaperman.

670
00:58:09,308 --> 00:58:10,775
That'd be quite a coup...

671
00:58:10,842 --> 00:58:13,971
bringing in your first story
wrapped around an assassin.

672
00:58:15,883 --> 00:58:19,444
I think I shall have to be
getting along now, Mr. Fisher.

673
00:58:19,653 --> 00:58:23,112
Shall we write the peace petition now
or leave it for later?

674
00:58:23,191 --> 00:58:26,320
We may as well do it straightaway,
in the study. Excuse us.

675
00:58:26,395 --> 00:58:30,025
Father, could I speak to you for a moment?
It's terribly important.

676
00:58:30,100 --> 00:58:31,692
This won't take a moment.

677
00:58:31,769 --> 00:58:35,261
Meanwhile, see if you can interest
Mr. Haverstock in some eggs and bacon.

678
00:58:35,340 --> 00:58:37,365
Mr. Fisher. What's that man doing here?

679
00:58:37,442 --> 00:58:38,671
<i>Why, it's Monsieur Krug.</i>

680
00:58:38,744 --> 00:58:40,837
- Van Meer isn't dead.
- I just read...

681
00:58:40,913 --> 00:58:44,577
That was his double that was shot.
Van Meer was kidnapped. I talked to him.

682
00:58:44,651 --> 00:58:46,244
<i>What has Monsieur Krug to do with it?</i>

683
00:58:46,320 --> 00:58:48,413
Remember my description
of the man in the mill?

684
00:58:48,489 --> 00:58:50,822
You mean the sweater. Of course.

685
00:58:50,892 --> 00:58:53,156
<i>That's impossible.
We've known Monsieur Krug...</i>

686
00:58:53,228 --> 00:58:56,859
Krug brought Van Meer here last night.
He's in England. They're hiding him.

687
00:58:56,933 --> 00:58:58,457
- You're positive?
- Of course.

688
00:58:58,535 --> 00:59:00,435
I was as close to Krug as I am to you now.

689
00:59:00,504 --> 00:59:03,838
It'd be terrible if we made a mistake.
But we can't allow him to...

690
00:59:03,908 --> 00:59:05,433
Leave it to me.

691
00:59:12,085 --> 00:59:14,714
I don't want to be inospitable,
but leave my house.

692
00:59:14,789 --> 00:59:18,453
Mr. Haverstock will suggest
that I turn you over to the police.

693
00:59:18,526 --> 00:59:21,860
Mr. Haverstock seems to be
something of a troublemaker.

694
00:59:21,930 --> 00:59:25,025
You said he'd been taken care of
by our agents in Amsterdam.

695
00:59:25,101 --> 00:59:28,367
I thought so, too. I don't understand it.

696
00:59:28,806 --> 00:59:31,275
Unless, perhaps,
Miss Fisher's being with him...

697
00:59:31,343 --> 00:59:33,277
may have caused complications.

698
00:59:33,513 --> 00:59:36,175
It would've been ideal
if she'd been in our confidences.

699
00:59:36,249 --> 00:59:39,219
- Please leave my daughter out of it.
- I beg your pardon.

700
00:59:39,285 --> 00:59:40,947
Most unfortunate, his coming here.

701
00:59:41,021 --> 00:59:44,719
I've never had to cope with this
sort of thing before, thanks to you, Krug.

702
00:59:44,793 --> 00:59:47,228
Someone has to take care
of the sordid details.

703
00:59:47,296 --> 00:59:49,491
This is close to home.
In fact, it is my home.

704
00:59:49,566 --> 00:59:52,557
After all, I'm only a politician. In a sense.

705
00:59:53,704 --> 00:59:56,674
And politicians aren't usually
called upon to...

706
00:59:57,442 --> 00:59:59,638
do away with their guests, are they?

707
01:00:00,279 --> 01:00:01,507
Quiet, boy.

708
01:00:01,580 --> 01:00:03,605
Not in the house. No, sir.

709
01:00:04,117 --> 01:00:05,675
But I have an idea.

710
01:00:12,493 --> 01:00:15,224
- Do you remember Rowley?
- Rowley?

711
01:00:15,732 --> 01:00:19,463
Yes. The little man that used to work
at your father's stables in Austria.

712
01:00:19,535 --> 01:00:23,438
I seem to recall he was present
when a mutual friend of ours...

713
01:00:23,674 --> 01:00:26,508
accidentally fell off
the high bridge at Bern.

714
01:00:26,578 --> 01:00:27,910
He's retired now.

715
01:00:27,980 --> 01:00:30,471
Lives somewhere in Clapham,
here in London.

716
01:00:30,816 --> 01:00:32,751
If Mr. Haverstock could be induced...

717
01:00:32,819 --> 01:00:35,686
to hire him in the capacity
of a private detective.

718
01:00:36,022 --> 01:00:37,285
What for?

719
01:00:38,326 --> 01:00:41,057
You should warn him
that it's very dangerous for him...

720
01:00:41,130 --> 01:00:44,361
to go about London
with the knowledge that he has.

721
01:00:45,502 --> 01:00:47,129
Yes, I see.

722
01:00:48,505 --> 01:00:51,066
You use the English language
with great delicacy.

723
01:00:51,142 --> 01:00:52,575
Thank you, sir.

724
01:00:52,643 --> 01:00:55,875
I shall look Mr. Rowley up at once
and give him his instructions.

725
01:00:56,214 --> 01:00:58,410
You mustrt. It would be too dangerous.

726
01:01:01,288 --> 01:01:03,415
What do we do now, call Scotland Yard?

727
01:01:03,490 --> 01:01:05,425
<i>I thought it best to send
Monsieur Krug away.</i>

728
01:01:05,492 --> 01:01:07,188
You let him get away? Listen...

729
01:01:07,262 --> 01:01:08,924
If what you say is true...

730
01:01:08,998 --> 01:01:11,626
then it's important not to rouse
Krug's suspicions.

731
01:01:11,700 --> 01:01:14,430
- Van Meer will be killed.
- Dead or alive, it's a story.

732
01:01:14,503 --> 01:01:16,063
Johnny, father's right.

733
01:01:16,139 --> 01:01:19,769
- Okay. I'll cable them what I've got.
- I wouldn't, if I were you.

734
01:01:19,844 --> 01:01:23,281
Van Meer's life may depend on
our keeping this quiet a few hours.

735
01:01:23,348 --> 01:01:24,747
Keep it quiet?

736
01:01:25,417 --> 01:01:29,115
A famous diplomat's kidnapped right
under my eyes and I muzzle myself?

737
01:01:29,189 --> 01:01:31,750
I'm sorry, but this is a story
with facts in it.

738
01:01:31,826 --> 01:01:35,558
This is the kind of story I'm here to get,
the kind America's waiting for.

739
01:01:35,630 --> 01:01:38,259
It'll be a bigger story if you can
wait a few hours...

740
01:01:38,334 --> 01:01:42,532
until we find Van Meer and discover
what's behind this curious business.

741
01:01:42,605 --> 01:01:44,096
I know what's behind it.

742
01:01:44,174 --> 01:01:47,440
I don't mean who is behind it.
I mean the why of it.

743
01:01:47,512 --> 01:01:50,949
Would you get me
all my correspondence with Krug?

744
01:01:51,417 --> 01:01:55,320
Do what Father says.
It'll be best for you and Mr. Van Meer.

745
01:01:55,722 --> 01:01:57,883
Okay. I'll wait.

746
01:02:01,629 --> 01:02:03,426
I'm worried about you, Mr. Haverstock.

747
01:02:03,498 --> 01:02:05,661
I'm worried about myself.
I feel weak-minded.

748
01:02:05,735 --> 01:02:09,102
You're right. I don't like you dashing about
without some protection.

749
01:02:09,172 --> 01:02:11,539
- Forget it.
- Lf you're right, you need protection.

750
01:02:11,609 --> 01:02:14,271
I've covered beer mob killings
and race riots...

751
01:02:14,345 --> 01:02:16,678
without even carrying a rabbit's foot.

752
01:02:16,748 --> 01:02:18,148
These people are criminals...

753
01:02:18,217 --> 01:02:21,084
more dangerous than your rumrunners
and house-breakers.

754
01:02:21,153 --> 01:02:22,553
They're fanatics.

755
01:02:22,623 --> 01:02:26,583
They combine a mad love of country
with an equally mad indifference to life...

756
01:02:26,660 --> 01:02:28,891
their own, as well as others'.

757
01:02:29,197 --> 01:02:33,760
They're cunning, unscrupulous
and inspired.

758
01:02:37,240 --> 01:02:40,539
I couldn't face Mr. Powers again
if you didn't live long enough...

759
01:02:40,611 --> 01:02:43,239
to turn in the best story of the year.

760
01:02:43,347 --> 01:02:46,374
I'm gonna be a fine foreign correspondent
hiding in an attic.

761
01:02:46,451 --> 01:02:50,218
I'm not suggesting you hide anywhere.
Just get somebody to protect you.

762
01:02:50,290 --> 01:02:53,021
A nurse? Johnny Jones goes to Europe
and hires a nurse.

763
01:02:53,093 --> 01:02:55,926
That's going to look great
on the expense account.

764
01:02:55,996 --> 01:03:00,093
I know a very efficient detective agency
where we can get just the man.

765
01:03:00,169 --> 01:03:03,435
- Okay. Whatever you say.
- I can arrange it for you.

766
01:03:04,541 --> 01:03:07,135
If you'll feel better, I won't mention it
to anybody.

767
01:03:07,210 --> 01:03:11,705
Mention it. If anyone finds out I've hired
a bodyguard, I'll shoot myself.

768
01:03:23,931 --> 01:03:26,662
If that's Mr. Rowley,
tell him to wait outside.

769
01:03:27,936 --> 01:03:31,600
I've called on Mr. Haverstock.
Will you tell him Mr. Rowley's here.

770
01:03:31,674 --> 01:03:34,142
- Yes. Will you wait here, please?
- Thank you.

771
01:03:36,313 --> 01:03:39,249
- Mr. Haverstock, your cab's here.
- Where are you going?

772
01:03:39,317 --> 01:03:42,378
- To the office, I've got work to do.
- You mustrt go.

773
01:03:42,454 --> 01:03:46,222
I was sent over here at great expense
as a newspaperman, not a refugee.

774
01:03:46,293 --> 01:03:49,160
- How about lunch at the Savoy?
- I'll see you out.

775
01:03:50,865 --> 01:03:53,994
- Johnny, please be careful.
- I'll be all right.

776
01:04:00,010 --> 01:04:02,535
- Mr. Haverstock?
- Is this the man?

777
01:04:02,613 --> 01:04:04,411
Look, who's protecting who?

778
01:04:04,483 --> 01:04:06,610
I ain't lanky, but I'm quick.

779
01:04:06,685 --> 01:04:09,017
You understand what you have to do?

780
01:04:09,087 --> 01:04:11,955
You can trust me to take good care
of Mr. Haverstock.

781
01:04:12,026 --> 01:04:15,154
- Are we going now, sir?
- Take me to my office in Fleet Street...

782
01:04:15,229 --> 01:04:18,529
- and if you're good, to the American Club.
- Right, sir.

783
01:04:18,600 --> 01:04:20,465
You'll keep after this other thing?

784
01:04:20,535 --> 01:04:24,131
When there's any definite news
of our friend, you can break the story.

785
01:04:24,206 --> 01:04:26,004
Goodbye.

786
01:04:31,749 --> 01:04:33,115
Why, Carol.

787
01:04:33,651 --> 01:04:36,712
Nothing must happen to him, Father.
I just couldn't...

788
01:04:43,130 --> 01:04:44,358
How do we go, sir?

789
01:04:44,432 --> 01:04:47,890
Should I walk a little behind you,
or beside you, like a friend?

790
01:04:47,969 --> 01:04:51,166
- What's the custom?
- People have different tastes.

791
01:04:51,239 --> 01:04:54,438
When I served the Duke of Albertson,
a democratic sort of gent...

792
01:04:54,511 --> 01:04:57,481
I used to walk alongside of him,
man-to-man like.

793
01:04:57,549 --> 01:05:00,278
I once had a lady who thought
that was disrespectful.

794
01:05:00,350 --> 01:05:03,149
"Three paces behind," she said.
"And don't smoke."

795
01:05:03,221 --> 01:05:06,350
What's good for a duke is good enough
for me. We can be a team.

796
01:05:06,425 --> 01:05:10,192
Thank you. If we want to go to
the American Club, we'd better take a cab.

797
01:05:10,263 --> 01:05:11,595
There's one.

798
01:05:12,266 --> 01:05:14,427
What's the trouble, sir?
Gangsters after you?

799
01:05:14,502 --> 01:05:15,697
Not exactly.

800
01:05:15,771 --> 01:05:19,707
We're not afraid of gangsters here.
Even our police don't carry guns.

801
01:05:19,775 --> 01:05:22,574
- What do they do?
- Biff you over the head with a stick.

802
01:05:22,645 --> 01:05:24,011
It's more healthy-like.

803
01:05:30,789 --> 01:05:33,725
Did you see that?
Someone deliberately pushed me.

804
01:05:33,793 --> 01:05:36,729
That was me. If I'd pulled you back,
you'd have been caught.

805
01:05:36,797 --> 01:05:40,256
- It was push or nothing.
- That's smart work, Mr. Rowley.

806
01:05:40,334 --> 01:05:43,100
- Thank you very much.
- That's what I'm here for.

807
01:05:43,172 --> 01:05:44,332
Taxi!

808
01:05:49,146 --> 01:05:51,172
- American Club.
- Yes, sir.

809
01:05:51,448 --> 01:05:52,780
After you, sir.

810
01:06:02,028 --> 01:06:03,427
I'm not certain, sir...

811
01:06:03,496 --> 01:06:07,194
but I've got an idea two men
took another cab to follow us.

812
01:06:07,568 --> 01:06:11,403
- I don't see anyone suspicious.
- I may have been mistaken...

813
01:06:11,707 --> 01:06:14,141
but I'm almost certain I saw them.

814
01:06:17,280 --> 01:06:19,909
They may have heard where we're going.

815
01:06:20,517 --> 01:06:21,678
Driver.

816
01:06:24,190 --> 01:06:27,057
Go down Victoria Street,
round past Buckingham Palace.

817
01:06:27,126 --> 01:06:28,491
Right, sir.

818
01:06:28,594 --> 01:06:31,723
We might give them the slip
if we go the long way around.

819
01:06:35,336 --> 01:06:37,134
I'm afraid they're still after us.

820
01:06:37,206 --> 01:06:40,903
Our best plan is to pull around
the corner and change cabs.

821
01:06:41,211 --> 01:06:44,146
Driver, take the first to your left
and pull up.

822
01:06:44,214 --> 01:06:45,841
We're going to walk a bit.

823
01:06:52,958 --> 01:06:56,225
I'll do it, sir. I understand the money.
It'll be quicker.

824
01:06:56,296 --> 01:06:57,524
Thank you, sir.

825
01:07:00,567 --> 01:07:03,366
I think our best plan
is to slip into the cathedral for a bit.

826
01:07:03,438 --> 01:07:07,034
Let's stop this ducking out of sight.
Let them catch up and have a showdown.

827
01:07:07,109 --> 01:07:10,841
No, I wouldn't cause a scene.
Our job is to give them the slip.

828
01:07:10,914 --> 01:07:12,575
All right. Let's go.

829
01:07:13,049 --> 01:07:15,348
Nice bit of architecture, sir.

830
01:07:42,019 --> 01:07:43,850
Do you want to go right in?

831
01:07:43,921 --> 01:07:47,222
I saw on the notice it was a requiem mass.
A mass for the dead.

832
01:07:47,659 --> 01:07:51,152
That sort of thing always depresses me,
praying for the dead.

833
01:07:51,230 --> 01:07:53,529
The dead are all right in their place...

834
01:07:53,600 --> 01:07:56,866
but the music and candles
always give me the creeps.

835
01:07:56,938 --> 01:08:00,067
Just really, sir.
I could be so frightened, sir, I...

836
01:08:05,114 --> 01:08:08,846
How about a trip up top, sir?
That'd really put them off the scent.

837
01:08:25,673 --> 01:08:27,504
Boys, careful there.

838
01:08:41,226 --> 01:08:44,423
- I can't see.
- Here, here.

839
01:08:45,098 --> 01:08:47,259
There you are, my boy!

840
01:08:49,470 --> 01:08:52,872
Look. There it goes. There!
I'll have to buy you another now.

841
01:08:54,909 --> 01:08:56,002
Love a duck!

842
01:08:56,078 --> 01:08:57,443
Careful, boys.

843
01:08:58,481 --> 01:09:00,540
You better be careful, too, sir.

844
01:09:05,757 --> 01:09:07,748
Not yet, boys. Come.

845
01:09:11,330 --> 01:09:14,823
Let's leave. I have a luncheon date
and plenty to do before.

846
01:09:14,901 --> 01:09:18,565
I've got it in mind, don't you worry.
Really, now. Look.

847
01:09:18,638 --> 01:09:23,168
Isn't it won'thwhile coming up here?
There's the Houses of Parliament there.

848
01:09:23,245 --> 01:09:26,704
And there's St. James' Park.
That green patch. Yeah.

849
01:09:26,783 --> 01:09:28,375
Come along, boys.

850
01:09:35,125 --> 01:09:38,824
You must excuse me getting scared
when you leaned over just now, sir.

851
01:09:38,898 --> 01:09:41,662
I was once with a man on a bridge
in Switzerland.

852
01:09:41,935 --> 01:09:43,926
He had a very nasty fall.

853
01:09:45,272 --> 01:09:47,536
Killed him. Stone dead.

854
01:09:49,745 --> 01:09:51,906
Always made me a bit nervous since.

855
01:10:07,633 --> 01:10:11,365
Don't go down just yet, sir.
I'd like you to see St. Paul's.

856
01:10:11,637 --> 01:10:13,868
There it is, just coming out of the mist.

857
01:10:13,942 --> 01:10:17,810
There's the horse guards approaching
Buckingham Palace. See them?

858
01:10:17,879 --> 01:10:21,748
It makes the back of me legs go funny.
Heights always did.

859
01:10:22,051 --> 01:10:23,450
Let's get down again, Eric.

860
01:10:23,519 --> 01:10:25,818
We've just come up.
Why didn't you say so before?

861
01:10:25,889 --> 01:10:27,857
Excuse me. I know just how you feel.

862
01:10:27,925 --> 01:10:30,986
Them as has no head for heights.
Nobody ought not to blame them.

863
01:10:31,062 --> 01:10:32,758
What's it got to do with you?

864
01:10:32,831 --> 01:10:36,131
All right, keep your hair on.
I was only sympathizing with the lady.

865
01:10:36,202 --> 01:10:38,102
- I'm going.
- Wait for the lift.

866
01:10:38,171 --> 01:10:39,196
No.

867
01:10:44,746 --> 01:10:47,909
No stairs for me.
I'm going to take the elevator.

868
01:10:48,284 --> 01:10:51,811
Wait a minute, sir.
You ain't seen the horse guards yet.

869
01:10:53,357 --> 01:10:55,826
You must see the horse guards, sir.

870
01:10:56,994 --> 01:11:00,523
- Where? I don't see anything.
- Why, there they are, sir.

871
01:11:01,400 --> 01:11:05,462
Down the road. Just going towards...

872
01:11:06,607 --> 01:11:08,336
the white building.

873
01:11:20,791 --> 01:11:22,452
No, boys. This way.

874
01:11:43,619 --> 01:11:45,986
There but for the grace of God.

875
01:11:46,056 --> 01:11:49,618
I still don't know what instinct made me
step aside when he came at me.

876
01:11:49,694 --> 01:11:51,218
You need a drink.

877
01:11:51,295 --> 01:11:54,093
I heard the lift coming up, and I turned.

878
01:11:54,199 --> 01:11:56,760
I saw that look in his eyes
as he came toward me.

879
01:11:56,836 --> 01:11:59,965
That split second, the whole thing
flashed through my mind.

880
01:12:00,040 --> 01:12:03,601
All I could think of was Fisher.
Fisher planned this.

881
01:12:05,512 --> 01:12:08,107
Then I guess I just stepped aside
and over he went.

882
01:12:08,184 --> 01:12:11,483
- Over he went all right. You want this?
- No, thanks.

883
01:12:12,154 --> 01:12:14,816
When are you going to send the story
to the gazette?

884
01:12:14,890 --> 01:12:16,222
When I get ready.

885
01:12:17,795 --> 01:12:19,854
There goes another one of my illusions.

886
01:12:19,931 --> 01:12:22,901
I thought you were one of the journalists
nothing could stop.

887
01:12:22,968 --> 01:12:25,995
Floods, smallpox, love:
The story must go on.

888
01:12:26,071 --> 01:12:27,266
It'll go on.

889
01:12:28,842 --> 01:12:29,831
No.

890
01:12:30,143 --> 01:12:33,080
I can understand you not wanting
to drag Miss Fisher into it...

891
01:12:33,147 --> 01:12:35,378
but she's probably in it already.

892
01:12:35,550 --> 01:12:37,711
- The moll of the gang.
- You dirty...

893
01:12:37,786 --> 01:12:40,881
On second thought,
I'm sure she's a fine girl...

894
01:12:40,957 --> 01:12:43,051
upstanding, honest, and a great soul.

895
01:12:43,127 --> 01:12:45,688
I can't send the story over
until Van Meer's safe.

896
01:12:45,763 --> 01:12:47,391
We got to find Van Meer first.

897
01:12:48,266 --> 01:12:51,429
There's our man now, probably.
Mr. Van Meer, come in.

898
01:12:53,206 --> 01:12:55,765
Good morning, Stebbins.
How are you, Haverstock?

899
01:12:55,842 --> 01:12:58,777
Congratulations on your little set-to
with Rowley.

900
01:13:00,515 --> 01:13:02,143
What do you know about Rowley?

901
01:13:02,217 --> 01:13:05,152
Very little ffolliott doesn't hear.
Probably knows about Fisher.

902
01:13:05,220 --> 01:13:07,211
I was onto Fisher a year ago.

903
01:13:07,324 --> 01:13:10,691
The fellow with the high neck sweater,
Krug, he's new to me.

904
01:13:10,760 --> 01:13:12,991
- You're onto him, too?
- I followed him to London.

905
01:13:13,064 --> 01:13:17,434
- I thought you were cold on this story.
- I've been doing some noticing.

906
01:13:17,502 --> 01:13:20,529
Remember that tramp
you found asleep in the mill?

907
01:13:20,606 --> 01:13:22,130
He wasrt a tramp at all.

908
01:13:22,208 --> 01:13:24,769
- Van Meer, I suppose.
- Not quite.

909
01:13:24,845 --> 01:13:27,313
But I notice him do
a strange thing for a tramp.

910
01:13:27,382 --> 01:13:30,909
He dirtied his hands
with some of that nasty Dutch soil.

911
01:13:31,052 --> 01:13:34,216
I can't follow the workings
of these masterminds.

912
01:13:36,325 --> 01:13:38,294
No. Tell him it's ridiculous.

913
01:13:40,298 --> 01:13:42,927
You'd already disappeared,
so I followed Krug...

914
01:13:43,000 --> 01:13:44,763
but found the same old mousetrap.

915
01:13:44,836 --> 01:13:47,032
- You mean Fisher?
- The good, kind...

916
01:13:47,106 --> 01:13:50,008
<i>genial head of the Peace Party,
Herr Fisher.</i>

917
01:13:51,645 --> 01:13:54,045
Hello, Eddy. This is Plunger Stebbins.

918
01:13:54,115 --> 01:13:57,210
I want to place a bet on
Flibbertigibbet in the first race...

919
01:13:57,285 --> 01:14:00,982
What? The race is over?
Okay, I'll call you later.

920
01:14:01,656 --> 01:14:04,524
Any objection to our working
this thing together?

921
01:14:04,594 --> 01:14:06,563
Catch Fisher, find Van Meer?

922
01:14:06,630 --> 01:14:09,827
Fine, but I'd like to know
why they kidnapped Van Meer.

923
01:14:09,901 --> 01:14:12,735
He was one of the signatories
to a certain treaty.

924
01:14:12,805 --> 01:14:15,296
The most important clause
was never written down...

925
01:14:15,374 --> 01:14:17,366
just memorized by the two signatories.

926
01:14:17,443 --> 01:14:19,139
And they'll beat it out of him?

927
01:14:19,212 --> 01:14:22,182
They'll try hard, and we should stop them.

928
01:14:22,250 --> 01:14:25,414
It contains a piece of information
very valuable to the enemy...

929
01:14:25,487 --> 01:14:28,116
in the war that starts tomorrow,
weather permitting.

930
01:14:28,190 --> 01:14:32,059
What? Why didn't somebody
let me in on this? Stebbins, let's get busy.

931
01:14:32,128 --> 01:14:33,618
Plenty of time. Lunch first.

932
01:14:33,697 --> 01:14:35,858
Wait a minute. You might be of help.

933
01:14:35,933 --> 01:14:39,199
I thought up a little plan
for forcing Fisher's hand.

934
01:14:39,271 --> 01:14:40,432
Let's have it.

935
01:14:40,505 --> 01:14:44,272
The neatest thing to do
would be to kidnap Fisher's daughter.

936
01:14:45,179 --> 01:14:46,270
Yeah?

937
01:14:46,346 --> 01:14:49,180
One of his few genuine traces of affection
is for Miss Fisher.

938
01:14:49,250 --> 01:14:51,411
Easy. You're speaking to a man in love.

939
01:14:51,486 --> 01:14:55,548
Good. Gives you a chance to get chummy,
to keep her happy at your side...

940
01:14:55,624 --> 01:14:58,651
while we batter old Papa.
This is my little scheme.

941
01:14:58,727 --> 01:15:02,187
I let Fisher know that his daughter is
in the hands of someone...

942
01:15:02,266 --> 01:15:05,099
who means business just as he does
when he kidnaps people...

943
01:15:05,169 --> 01:15:07,297
- and he'll see things our way.
- Nothing doing.

944
01:15:07,372 --> 01:15:08,862
Arert you a newspaperman?

945
01:15:08,942 --> 01:15:13,140
- That doesn't include kidnapping fiancées.
- It would, if your country were at stake.

946
01:15:13,213 --> 01:15:15,978
- This isn't my country.
- It's your story. Don't be gloomy.

947
01:15:16,050 --> 01:15:18,951
She doesn't have to know
what you're doing. Keep her amused.

948
01:15:19,019 --> 01:15:21,147
Why not grab Fisher, have a showdown?

949
01:15:21,223 --> 01:15:23,658
That's no good.
We've got nothing on Fisher.

950
01:15:23,726 --> 01:15:28,255
He'd slip out of it. He has been for years.
We'd merely kill Van Meer.

951
01:15:30,168 --> 01:15:33,604
Darling, are you all right?
Why were you on the tower?

952
01:15:33,671 --> 01:15:35,572
Keeping safe, I thought.

953
01:15:35,641 --> 01:15:38,611
Those assassins followed,
there was a scuffle, and over he went.

954
01:15:38,678 --> 01:15:42,910
They won't stop till they get you.
You must leave London immediately.

955
01:15:45,920 --> 01:15:49,015
The one thing everybody forgets
is that I'm a reporter.

956
01:15:49,091 --> 01:15:52,619
- And there's a war. I can't run from it.
- He can't stay here.

957
01:15:52,695 --> 01:15:56,223
- Tell him how desperate they are.
- Don't stay here, why don't you take him?

958
01:15:56,300 --> 01:15:57,358
I won't go.

959
01:15:57,435 --> 01:16:00,062
Isn't there some maiden aunt
in the country?

960
01:16:00,137 --> 01:16:03,972
- My Aunt Margaret. Let me take you there.
- How about it?

961
01:16:04,042 --> 01:16:07,377
- Stay out of this.
- It's the only sensible thing to do.

962
01:16:07,613 --> 01:16:09,606
May I use your telephone?

963
01:16:16,992 --> 01:16:19,359
Hello, Stiles. Miss Carol speaking.

964
01:16:19,429 --> 01:16:22,990
Please tell Mr. Fisher I'm driving
to my Aunt Margaret's at Harpenden.

965
01:16:23,066 --> 01:16:27,128
- I don't care what you arrange. I won't go.
- I'll be back for dinner. Thank you.

966
01:16:27,204 --> 01:16:30,573
- It's all settled. We'll get you a toothbrush.
- Carol, it's no good.

967
01:16:30,643 --> 01:16:33,008
I wonder if this idea of your aunt
is so good.

968
01:16:33,079 --> 01:16:35,274
Maybe you should go further,
say, Cambridge.

969
01:16:35,348 --> 01:16:37,340
No place is as obscure as Harpenden.

970
01:16:37,417 --> 01:16:40,786
It's not the place, but that Krug
might connect you with it.

971
01:16:40,855 --> 01:16:44,916
- Maybe so. Let's make it Cambridge.
- I'll phone your father so he doesn't worry.

972
01:16:44,994 --> 01:16:47,258
Thank you. Please, Johnny.

973
01:16:58,744 --> 01:17:02,476
That was a break, her coming,
and suggesting they go to the country.

974
01:17:02,549 --> 01:17:04,381
As a matter of fact, old boy...

975
01:17:04,452 --> 01:17:08,048
I suggested it to her on the phone
about half an hour ago.

976
01:17:16,566 --> 01:17:20,059
There hasn't been a sign of anybody
for the last 30 miles.

977
01:17:20,904 --> 01:17:23,032
- What's the matter?
- Nothing.

978
01:17:23,375 --> 01:17:27,039
At least talk to me.
It's unfair of you to sit and pout...

979
01:17:27,113 --> 01:17:29,947
because I've kidnapped you
from your so-called duties.

980
01:17:30,017 --> 01:17:31,746
You've kidnapped me?

981
01:17:31,818 --> 01:17:33,616
Just remember that.

982
01:17:33,688 --> 01:17:35,121
Please forgive me.

983
01:17:35,188 --> 01:17:38,557
Sure. I don't think kidnapping's anything
to get sore about...

984
01:17:38,627 --> 01:17:41,391
- when the right kidnapper does it. Do you?
- Not at all.

985
01:17:41,463 --> 01:17:42,223
Thanks.

986
01:17:49,774 --> 01:17:50,935
Hello?

987
01:17:52,678 --> 01:17:55,273
No, Mr. Ffolliott, I'm afraid he's not in yet.

988
01:17:56,249 --> 01:17:57,547
Very well, sir.

989
01:18:09,999 --> 01:18:12,195
- Johnny, you don't love me.
- You're crazy.

990
01:18:12,269 --> 01:18:15,865
- You looked unappy kissing me.
- Never happier in my life.

991
01:18:15,940 --> 01:18:18,306
Wort do. Johnny, what's happened?

992
01:18:18,376 --> 01:18:21,312
I don't know.
They say war's coming tomorrow.

993
01:18:21,380 --> 01:18:23,975
You've changed your philosophy
since yesterday.

994
01:18:24,050 --> 01:18:26,450
There are more important things
than love.

995
01:18:26,520 --> 01:18:29,149
I've got lots to do, important things.

996
01:18:29,391 --> 01:18:31,824
Got to start.
It'll take three hours to get back.

997
01:18:31,893 --> 01:18:35,386
Don't misunderstand me.
I'm so love with you, I'm going mad.

998
01:18:35,464 --> 01:18:37,956
Wort do. I guess it can't be helped.

999
01:18:38,034 --> 01:18:41,163
- You've turned European overnight.
- That's unfair.

1000
01:18:41,238 --> 01:18:44,299
I'm just as big a jackass as ever. Bigger.

1001
01:18:44,909 --> 01:18:47,139
You're not going back to London to dinner.

1002
01:18:47,212 --> 01:18:49,841
You can't run out on your kidnapper.

1003
01:18:50,249 --> 01:18:52,843
I mean, you know what I mean.

1004
01:18:53,420 --> 01:18:57,482
If you leave, I'll go back to London
and let them bump me off.

1005
01:18:58,527 --> 01:19:01,257
- It'll be a relief at that.
- You are moody.

1006
01:19:02,131 --> 01:19:03,895
Am I the cause of it?

1007
01:19:05,969 --> 01:19:09,167
If you knew how much I loved you,
you'd faint.

1008
01:19:17,049 --> 01:19:19,348
There. What'd I tell you?

1009
01:19:20,854 --> 01:19:22,014
Come in.

1010
01:19:22,589 --> 01:19:23,852
- Mr. Haverstock?
- Yes?

1011
01:19:23,925 --> 01:19:25,051
Call from London.

1012
01:19:25,126 --> 01:19:28,562
- Have them switch it here.
- The only phone here is in the office.

1013
01:19:28,630 --> 01:19:30,155
All right. I'll come down.

1014
01:19:31,000 --> 01:19:33,264
Forgive me for a moment, dear.

1015
01:19:40,111 --> 01:19:41,840
Just a moment, sir.

1016
01:19:48,855 --> 01:19:51,416
- Hello?
- Is that you, Haverstock?

1017
01:19:51,492 --> 01:19:54,860
Are you alone? Can you talk?
I can't reach Fisher.

1018
01:19:54,996 --> 01:19:56,930
He's been out all afternoon.

1019
01:19:57,633 --> 01:20:00,967
You'll have to keep the girl there
much longer than we planned.

1020
01:20:01,038 --> 01:20:03,973
I don't know when he'll return.
I've got to catch him alone.

1021
01:20:04,041 --> 01:20:06,134
Better keep her there
for the rest of the night.

1022
01:20:06,344 --> 01:20:08,609
That's absolutely impossible.

1023
01:20:08,980 --> 01:20:11,381
We can't let this thing go now.

1024
01:20:12,318 --> 01:20:16,221
I can't very well explain,
but I couldn't pull a thing like that.

1025
01:20:16,289 --> 01:20:19,782
There's nothing else to be done.
I'm counting on you.

1026
01:20:20,862 --> 01:20:21,955
Hello?

1027
01:20:35,547 --> 01:20:37,743
Are you quite satisfied
with your room, sir?

1028
01:20:37,817 --> 01:20:41,219
Not exactly. I mean, yes...

1029
01:20:41,288 --> 01:20:43,984
But what I really wanted
was another room as well.

1030
01:20:44,057 --> 01:20:45,490
A single room.

1031
01:20:47,962 --> 01:20:51,091
Mr. Naysmith, this gentleman wants
another room.

1032
01:20:51,433 --> 01:20:54,095
Is it for the lady
and how long do you need it?

1033
01:20:54,169 --> 01:20:56,900
She'll only be here just the one night.

1034
01:21:00,077 --> 01:21:03,070
- The gentleman has Number 7.
- What about Number 8?

1035
01:21:03,148 --> 01:21:07,483
It doesn't really make any difference.
Just a good room, windows and all that.

1036
01:21:07,553 --> 01:21:09,248
I understand.

1037
01:21:09,323 --> 01:21:12,451
Perhaps the room next to yours
would be best.

1038
01:21:12,526 --> 01:21:15,724
It's quite a cozy room, isn't it, Number 8?

1039
01:21:15,797 --> 01:21:18,892
- They're all alike to me, sir.
- Eight will do.

1040
01:21:19,101 --> 01:21:21,695
Will you bring the lady down
to sign the book, please?

1041
01:21:21,771 --> 01:21:24,206
Yes, I'll get her.

1042
01:21:43,531 --> 01:21:45,796
- Good evening, sir.
- Good evening.

1043
01:21:51,341 --> 01:21:54,608
Terrible thing, sir, that poor man
who was here this morning.

1044
01:21:54,979 --> 01:21:58,245
- Yes, terrible. My bags all packed?
- Yes, sir.

1045
01:21:58,316 --> 01:21:59,749
What about Miss Carol's?

1046
01:21:59,818 --> 01:22:03,220
Mrs. Stiles packed hers, too. She hopes
she's put in the right things.

1047
01:22:03,289 --> 01:22:05,850
It's been a rush, as she's not back yet.

1048
01:22:06,360 --> 01:22:08,760
Mr. Ffolliott's waiting in the sitting room.

1049
01:22:09,163 --> 01:22:11,962
Another gentleman phoned,
but wouldn't leave his name.

1050
01:22:12,034 --> 01:22:15,265
I thought he sounded
like the foreign gentleman at breakfast.

1051
01:22:15,572 --> 01:22:18,542
- Did he say he'd telephone again?
- Yes. He said it was urgent.

1052
01:22:18,608 --> 01:22:21,134
Well, show Mr. Ffolliott into the study.

1053
01:22:38,933 --> 01:22:41,903
- Hello, sir.
- You caught me at a very busy moment.

1054
01:22:41,970 --> 01:22:44,201
I'm going to America tomorrow.

1055
01:22:44,273 --> 01:22:45,866
Are you taking Carol with you?

1056
01:22:45,942 --> 01:22:49,572
Yes, she doesn't know yet.
It's been a rush. I'm waiting for her.

1057
01:22:50,213 --> 01:22:53,274
Scott, what's your worry?
Must be important.

1058
01:22:53,351 --> 01:22:55,980
Yes, it is rather important.
It's about Carol.

1059
01:22:56,055 --> 01:22:58,717
- I'm afraid that...
- What? Anything happen to her?

1060
01:22:58,791 --> 01:23:02,193
No, but I don't think you'll be able to
take her with you to America.

1061
01:23:02,596 --> 01:23:03,824
Why not?

1062
01:23:05,200 --> 01:23:08,500
I know it'll sound rather silly to you,
but Carol's been kidnapped.

1063
01:23:08,870 --> 01:23:11,066
- Is this a joke of some sort?
- No, sir.

1064
01:23:11,808 --> 01:23:13,673
What do you mean, kidnapped?

1065
01:23:13,743 --> 01:23:16,440
I happen to know she's with her aunt
in Harpenden.

1066
01:23:16,513 --> 01:23:18,141
I'm afraid she isn't.

1067
01:23:30,464 --> 01:23:33,833
Who gave you the message that
Miss Carol's gone to her Aunt Margaret's?

1068
01:23:33,902 --> 01:23:35,596
Miss Carol herself, sir.

1069
01:23:36,872 --> 01:23:37,999
Thank you.

1070
01:23:38,575 --> 01:23:40,942
That's where she thought she was going.

1071
01:23:49,921 --> 01:23:52,413
Get me Harpenden, 43422.

1072
01:23:55,329 --> 01:23:58,629
Hello. Is that you, Margaret?
Is Carol with you?

1073
01:24:03,372 --> 01:24:06,000
No. I wasrt certain.

1074
01:24:06,076 --> 01:24:08,306
She said she might run down to see you.

1075
01:24:08,378 --> 01:24:10,903
I didn't know whether to expect
her back for dinner.

1076
01:24:11,382 --> 01:24:13,475
All right. Good night, Margaret.

1077
01:24:16,420 --> 01:24:17,912
No, she isn't there.

1078
01:24:19,959 --> 01:24:22,621
What makes you say
she's been kidnapped?

1079
01:24:23,630 --> 01:24:26,691
Sir, I arranged it.

1080
01:24:30,272 --> 01:24:33,071
Ffolliott, this has gone far enough.
Where is Carol?

1081
01:24:33,709 --> 01:24:36,234
Carol's being held as a sort of hostage...

1082
01:24:36,680 --> 01:24:39,012
by some people
who are very much in earnest...

1083
01:24:39,082 --> 01:24:41,175
as much in earnest as you are.

1084
01:24:41,686 --> 01:24:45,350
Don't be so cryptic.
I haven't the faintest idea what you mean.

1085
01:24:48,194 --> 01:24:50,755
I want to know
where you're hiding Van Meer.

1086
01:24:54,268 --> 01:24:58,365
So that's it. You've been talking
with that American, Haverstock.

1087
01:24:58,440 --> 01:25:01,273
He told me something about Van Meer
being alive.

1088
01:25:01,343 --> 01:25:03,677
You promised Haverstock
you'd look into it.

1089
01:25:03,747 --> 01:25:04,736
Naturally.

1090
01:25:04,814 --> 01:25:08,046
Unusual way of looking into it,
trying to put him out of the way.

1091
01:25:08,118 --> 01:25:11,452
I realize a life's a small matter,
the way you work.

1092
01:25:11,690 --> 01:25:15,491
The people who've got Carol
can take a leaf out of your book.

1093
01:25:18,665 --> 01:25:20,691
Where is she? What've you done with her?

1094
01:25:20,768 --> 01:25:22,292
Where's Van Meer?

1095
01:25:30,847 --> 01:25:32,007
Hello.

1096
01:25:32,082 --> 01:25:36,019
I can get our Dutch friend to talk
if you come along yourself.

1097
01:25:36,354 --> 01:25:40,758
Sorry to drag you here, but it's the only
way if you want to leave tomorrow.

1098
01:25:41,461 --> 01:25:45,990
When you get here,
ask at the cashier's desk to use the phone.

1099
01:25:46,466 --> 01:25:48,230
They'll show you straight up.

1100
01:25:50,472 --> 01:25:52,532
I'll drop in as soon as I can.

1101
01:25:52,874 --> 01:25:56,676
If you want Carol to go with you,
better tell me where Van Meer is.

1102
01:25:56,747 --> 01:25:58,544
Bring her here, I'll give you the address.

1103
01:25:58,614 --> 01:26:01,881
Carol can be home in three hours.
I want that address now.

1104
01:26:02,020 --> 01:26:04,545
You can have it as soon as Carol's home.

1105
01:26:04,622 --> 01:26:06,648
I can't possibly wait three hours.

1106
01:26:06,725 --> 01:26:09,558
Besides, I happen to want Van Meer alive.

1107
01:26:39,433 --> 01:26:42,402
- Scott, I delivered him all right.
- Good.

1108
01:26:43,304 --> 01:26:45,204
I think I'll be getting along.

1109
01:26:45,273 --> 01:26:48,710
Thanks very much for those points.
Can I take them now?

1110
01:26:49,111 --> 01:26:50,908
Good night, Carol.

1111
01:27:13,208 --> 01:27:16,610
This isn't like you.
What is it that upsets you so?

1112
01:27:16,946 --> 01:27:20,474
I know I'm being silly.
I'm behaving perfectly stupidly.

1113
01:27:20,784 --> 01:27:22,274
Please forgive me.

1114
01:27:23,420 --> 01:27:24,854
I wouldn't mind so much...

1115
01:27:24,922 --> 01:27:27,391
but I didn't think
he was that sort of person.

1116
01:27:29,962 --> 01:27:32,454
Something to do with young Haverstock?

1117
01:27:33,366 --> 01:27:35,027
You like him very much.

1118
01:27:35,602 --> 01:27:38,264
After what happened,
I drove him to the country...

1119
01:27:38,339 --> 01:27:40,273
to get him away from those people.

1120
01:27:40,642 --> 01:27:43,008
I thought you were going
to Aunt Margaret's.

1121
01:27:43,078 --> 01:27:44,943
We were, but Scott ffolliott...

1122
01:27:45,013 --> 01:27:47,312
thought it would be better
to go further away.

1123
01:27:50,287 --> 01:27:54,019
So I thought The College Arms
at Cambridge would be a good place.

1124
01:27:54,492 --> 01:27:57,053
When we got there,
I found out that he wanted...

1125
01:27:58,130 --> 01:28:00,599
You see, we'd been joking about it.

1126
01:28:01,468 --> 01:28:05,030
When I heard him book the extra room,
I knew he meant it.

1127
01:28:06,073 --> 01:28:09,167
Cheap trick. That's what hurts.
It was so cheap.

1128
01:28:09,778 --> 01:28:12,008
It wasrt at all like I thought it was.

1129
01:28:13,516 --> 01:28:16,974
What difference does it make,
I don't care if I ever see him again.

1130
01:28:17,053 --> 01:28:20,046
You won't have to. We're going
to America tomorrow by clipper.

1131
01:28:20,125 --> 01:28:22,116
Tomorrow? But I can't.

1132
01:28:23,995 --> 01:28:26,556
I suppose I can, but why tomorrow?

1133
01:28:26,632 --> 01:28:29,192
They'll probably declare war tomorrow.

1134
01:28:29,268 --> 01:28:31,794
We have to get to Washington.
The boats will be crowded.

1135
01:28:31,872 --> 01:28:33,807
We may have to wait two weeks
for passage.

1136
01:28:33,874 --> 01:28:37,367
- But what about Mr. Van Meer?
- We've done all we could.

1137
01:28:37,679 --> 01:28:41,776
I was at the foreign office.
They're taking the whole thing over.

1138
01:28:42,652 --> 01:28:45,348
- What is it?
- The blackout. I have to draw the blinds.

1139
01:28:45,422 --> 01:28:48,654
I forgot. Before you do that,
order me a taxi.

1140
01:28:48,726 --> 01:28:49,852
Yes, sir.

1141
01:28:50,796 --> 01:28:53,230
There are some people I must see
before we leave.

1142
01:28:53,298 --> 01:28:55,892
I shouldn't be long.
Mrs. Stiles has done your packing.

1143
01:28:55,969 --> 01:28:59,064
We'll drive to Southampton,
stay overnight at the Southwestern.

1144
01:28:59,139 --> 01:29:00,299
Stiles, my hat.

1145
01:29:00,374 --> 01:29:02,775
Goodbye, darling.
I'll return as soon as possible.

1146
01:29:02,843 --> 01:29:06,644
Meanwhile, you and Stiles load the car
and get something to eat.

1147
01:29:06,715 --> 01:29:09,617
- But what about you?
- I'll get a sandwich later.

1148
01:29:18,564 --> 01:29:21,761
242 Charlotte Street,
at the top of Tottenam Court Road.

1149
01:29:30,979 --> 01:29:34,142
Wait here until Haverstock turns up.
He's bound to come here.

1150
01:29:34,216 --> 01:29:36,845
When he does, bring him to
242, Charlotte Street...

1151
01:29:36,920 --> 01:29:38,615
off of Tottenam Court Road.

1152
01:30:26,114 --> 01:30:27,411
Be careful.

1153
01:30:40,064 --> 01:30:41,930
Might I use your telephone?

1154
01:30:42,467 --> 01:30:43,959
This way, sir.

1155
01:31:04,495 --> 01:31:05,986
- Where is he?
- In there.

1156
01:31:06,063 --> 01:31:08,498
We can't make him say anything.
It's up to you.

1157
01:31:08,567 --> 01:31:11,092
Let's go. Is this place safe?

1158
01:31:11,170 --> 01:31:13,798
There'll be no interruptions.
We close it for decorations.

1159
01:31:13,873 --> 01:31:16,468
- The people downstairs?
- They won't make trouble.

1160
01:31:16,544 --> 01:31:19,945
They know what will happen
to their relatives if they do.

1161
01:31:47,048 --> 01:31:50,280
It's an attractive nest, I know,
and the music...

1162
01:31:50,352 --> 01:31:53,083
- It serves its purpose.
- Yes.

1163
01:32:12,446 --> 01:32:13,538
Pardon me.

1164
01:32:18,920 --> 01:32:22,289
Put your arm around him.
Hold his head forward.

1165
01:32:25,362 --> 01:32:27,523
These lights, can't you cut them down?

1166
01:32:34,874 --> 01:32:36,273
I thank you.

1167
01:32:37,677 --> 01:32:39,805
I thank you very much.

1168
01:32:43,651 --> 01:32:46,450
You're like my friend Mr. Fisher.

1169
01:32:47,222 --> 01:32:50,522
I'm sorry. It's just so dark...

1170
01:32:53,364 --> 01:32:55,025
I can't tell...

1171
01:32:57,202 --> 01:33:00,399
but you are so like my friend.

1172
01:33:00,673 --> 01:33:03,575
I am Fisher, Mr. Van Meer.
I am your friend.

1173
01:33:05,578 --> 01:33:07,171
I'm so glad.

1174
01:33:08,316 --> 01:33:10,614
Are the police here?

1175
01:33:11,319 --> 01:33:13,344
They mustrt get away.

1176
01:33:13,822 --> 01:33:16,486
You mustrt let these people go.

1177
01:33:19,729 --> 01:33:23,826
I represent Jupiter Life Insurance.
Would you like a small policy?

1178
01:33:29,708 --> 01:33:32,543
- Why did you bring him up here?
- I didn't know what to do.

1179
01:33:32,613 --> 01:33:35,047
I'd gladly relieve the lady
of this embarrassment.

1180
01:33:35,115 --> 01:33:37,983
You know how women are with firearms,
no sense of timing.

1181
01:33:38,053 --> 01:33:40,886
I'll just sit here. You carry on with
what you were doing.

1182
01:33:40,957 --> 01:33:43,858
Don't mind me.
I sometimes sit like this for hours.

1183
01:33:44,193 --> 01:33:45,627
Who's that?

1184
01:33:45,896 --> 01:33:47,727
Is it the police?

1185
01:33:48,632 --> 01:33:51,329
Tell me where I am.

1186
01:33:51,669 --> 01:33:53,797
You are in London, Mr. Van Meer.

1187
01:33:53,873 --> 01:33:55,238
In London?

1188
01:33:56,275 --> 01:33:58,210
Have I been here long?

1189
01:34:00,013 --> 01:34:04,280
You must send a telegram to my wife.

1190
01:34:04,352 --> 01:34:06,820
Tell her that I am safe with you.

1191
01:34:06,889 --> 01:34:09,983
Please try to understand, Mr. Van Meer.
The police are not here.

1192
01:34:10,058 --> 01:34:12,254
I am here merely to talk to you.

1193
01:34:12,896 --> 01:34:15,388
But these people...

1194
01:34:15,766 --> 01:34:19,203
They think I'm working with them.
They don't know that I'm your friend.

1195
01:34:19,437 --> 01:34:21,462
We must play a little game.

1196
01:34:21,573 --> 01:34:23,165
A little game?

1197
01:34:23,308 --> 01:34:26,575
Yes. They've asked me
to get you to tell me...

1198
01:34:26,647 --> 01:34:28,547
what they're trying to find out.

1199
01:34:28,615 --> 01:34:30,914
But I can't do that.

1200
01:34:31,519 --> 01:34:33,282
You know that I can't.

1201
01:34:33,621 --> 01:34:35,317
You can tell me.

1202
01:34:36,025 --> 01:34:39,757
Just that one clause in the treaty.
Clause 27.

1203
01:34:40,897 --> 01:34:44,664
Clause 27. Come, Mr. Van Meer.

1204
01:34:45,136 --> 01:34:47,901
That's the secret clause.

1205
01:34:48,674 --> 01:34:51,768
I know it, Clause 27.

1206
01:34:52,478 --> 01:34:54,845
But they, they mustrt know it.

1207
01:34:55,115 --> 01:34:57,743
It would help them if they make war.

1208
01:34:57,818 --> 01:34:59,377
War, Fisher.

1209
01:34:59,788 --> 01:35:02,587
- You don't want them helped, do you?
- Of course not.

1210
01:35:03,558 --> 01:35:07,189
Just let them see you telling it to me.
That'll be enough.

1211
01:35:07,697 --> 01:35:10,360
Let them see you whisper it to me.

1212
01:35:10,902 --> 01:35:13,132
I'll promise to keep it safe.

1213
01:35:13,705 --> 01:35:16,469
He's not your friend, Mr. Van Meer.
Don't tell him.

1214
01:35:17,042 --> 01:35:18,441
Who's that?

1215
01:35:19,212 --> 01:35:22,238
Someone just said you werert my friend.

1216
01:35:24,151 --> 01:35:26,551
Why didn't you bring the police?

1217
01:35:27,154 --> 01:35:30,386
Why aren't you taking me away from here?

1218
01:35:33,128 --> 01:35:35,724
You are not to take me away.

1219
01:35:36,866 --> 01:35:37,992
Why?

1220
01:35:46,312 --> 01:35:47,746
Where are you?

1221
01:35:48,814 --> 01:35:51,545
Help me.

1222
01:35:55,423 --> 01:35:56,618
That's it.

1223
01:35:57,993 --> 01:35:59,483
I see now.

1224
01:36:00,529 --> 01:36:03,931
There's no help. No help...

1225
01:36:04,568 --> 01:36:09,438
for the whole poor suffering world.

1226
01:36:12,944 --> 01:36:15,505
You cry peace, Fisher.

1227
01:36:16,082 --> 01:36:19,416
Peace. And there was no peace.

1228
01:36:19,887 --> 01:36:23,551
Only war and death.

1229
01:36:24,159 --> 01:36:26,559
You're a liar, Fisher.

1230
01:36:27,563 --> 01:36:29,861
A cruel liar.

1231
01:36:31,668 --> 01:36:34,638
You can do what you want with me.

1232
01:36:35,073 --> 01:36:37,064
That's not important.

1233
01:36:37,642 --> 01:36:41,512
But you'll never conquer them, Fisher.

1234
01:36:42,749 --> 01:36:45,115
Little people everywhere...

1235
01:36:45,586 --> 01:36:47,850
who give crumbs to birds.

1236
01:36:49,257 --> 01:36:50,724
Lie to them.

1237
01:36:52,394 --> 01:36:54,863
Drive them, whip them...

1238
01:36:55,765 --> 01:36:58,428
force them into war.

1239
01:36:59,303 --> 01:37:02,033
When the beasts like you...

1240
01:37:02,106 --> 01:37:04,905
will devour each other...

1241
01:37:06,377 --> 01:37:08,403
then the world...

1242
01:37:10,182 --> 01:37:13,118
will belong to the little people.

1243
01:37:13,854 --> 01:37:15,584
We're wasting valuable time.

1244
01:37:45,260 --> 01:37:49,129
All right. I will tell you...

1245
01:37:51,334 --> 01:37:53,632
I will tell everything.

1246
01:37:54,171 --> 01:37:55,969
Come on, Mr. Fisher.

1247
01:37:58,309 --> 01:38:01,677
In the event of invasion by an enemy...

1248
01:38:05,685 --> 01:38:07,346
Why, it's only a restaurant.

1249
01:38:07,721 --> 01:38:09,382
Look! Come on!

1250
01:38:10,391 --> 01:38:12,791
This way. Down the back stairs.

1251
01:38:37,725 --> 01:38:38,885
Follow me.

1252
01:38:55,080 --> 01:38:56,844
They must've gone the other way.

1253
01:38:56,916 --> 01:38:58,177
Look after him.

1254
01:39:08,354 --> 01:39:10,789
You're a blithering idiot
if you don't nab Fisher...

1255
01:39:10,858 --> 01:39:12,291
before he boards that plane.

1256
01:39:12,359 --> 01:39:14,521
How can we arrest him
without any evidence?

1257
01:39:14,596 --> 01:39:17,088
You're obstinate.
Isn't Van Meer proof enough?

1258
01:39:17,165 --> 01:39:18,826
No, and you ought to know it.

1259
01:39:18,900 --> 01:39:20,926
What proof is there against
Fisher personally?

1260
01:39:21,003 --> 01:39:22,971
Of all the conceited, stupid numbskull...

1261
01:39:23,039 --> 01:39:26,100
Stop behaving like a boy scout
and let us handle this.

1262
01:39:26,443 --> 01:39:28,002
Ask McKenna to come in.

1263
01:39:28,079 --> 01:39:30,947
Go see Dr. Boniface.
He's very good for nerves.

1264
01:39:31,016 --> 01:39:33,416
- Identification of Van Meer complete?
- Yes.

1265
01:39:33,485 --> 01:39:36,978
He's unconscious, but there's no doubt
it's Van Meer.

1266
01:39:37,056 --> 01:39:38,388
You'd better get back.

1267
01:39:38,459 --> 01:39:41,690
Take somebody along to get a statement
when he comes to.

1268
01:39:42,030 --> 01:39:44,328
Meanwhile, keep an eye
on that flying boat...

1269
01:39:44,398 --> 01:39:45,991
await instructions from us.

1270
01:39:46,168 --> 01:39:48,501
What's the good of being related
to Scotland Yard?

1271
01:39:48,571 --> 01:39:52,302
- My fool brother won't do anything.
- Scotland Yard can't solve my problems.

1272
01:39:52,375 --> 01:39:55,539
- Everyone's in on it but me.
- You're in it, too.

1273
01:39:55,613 --> 01:39:59,606
We've got to watch that plane.
While we're driving...

1274
01:39:59,684 --> 01:40:02,882
- ring Mayfair 24574.
- Let me write that.

1275
01:40:02,955 --> 01:40:06,414
Mayfair 24574. That's my cousin.
He's the director of the airline.

1276
01:40:06,494 --> 01:40:10,328
Tell him we need two seats
on tomorrow's clipper to America.

1277
01:40:10,399 --> 01:40:13,196
Then go to Hilton Nursing Home
and stick by Van Meer.

1278
01:40:13,268 --> 01:40:16,295
Then phone Miss Edith Armbruster,
Kensington 66255.

1279
01:40:16,372 --> 01:40:17,805
Tell her I'm off to America.

1280
01:40:17,874 --> 01:40:21,743
Will she dine with me next Monday
instead of tomorrow?

1281
01:40:21,812 --> 01:40:24,111
<i>- Sure.
- Then call up Stevens at the Post.</i>

1282
01:40:24,182 --> 01:40:26,207
Tell him I'm off to America.

1283
01:40:26,284 --> 01:40:28,981
Cable New York,
tell them I'm off to America.

1284
01:40:29,054 --> 01:40:32,253
Ring up the Crescent Dancing Academy
and cancel my rumba lesson.

1285
01:40:33,126 --> 01:40:35,652
Two ham sandwiches on rye bread.

1286
01:40:37,799 --> 01:40:41,997
- There's no use in my waiting around.
- It's hard to say how soon he'll recover.

1287
01:40:42,071 --> 01:40:44,005
It may be some hours before he can speak.

1288
01:40:44,073 --> 01:40:46,975
I don't know much about this,
but my friend's on the clipper.

1289
01:40:47,043 --> 01:40:50,309
If Van Meer speaks,
they'll send word to the plane.

1290
01:40:50,381 --> 01:40:52,111
Did you hear the wireless?

1291
01:40:52,184 --> 01:40:54,709
War is declared! Read all about it.

1292
01:40:56,488 --> 01:40:59,687
War declared! It's war with Germany!

1293
01:41:30,364 --> 01:41:32,525
I found that picture.

1294
01:41:48,486 --> 01:41:51,354
- Steward, bring me one of those, please.
- Yes, sir.

1295
01:42:23,163 --> 01:42:25,097
- Any message for me?
- What name?

1296
01:42:25,165 --> 01:42:28,033
- Is there a message for me?
- I'll be with you in a minute.

1297
01:42:30,171 --> 01:42:32,072
- This one's for me.
- Yes, sir.

1298
01:42:46,058 --> 01:42:47,548
Lovely, isn't it?

1299
01:42:47,627 --> 01:42:50,528
Sort of makes you forget
all about the war and troubles.

1300
01:42:51,699 --> 01:42:56,137
It would be nice if we could keep flying,
live in the clouds.

1301
01:42:56,638 --> 01:42:58,538
Yes, it would be very nice.

1302
01:43:00,043 --> 01:43:04,173
It's time for me to make a landing,
a forced landing.

1303
01:43:05,082 --> 01:43:07,312
What's the matter? Anything happen?

1304
01:43:07,585 --> 01:43:10,452
I've got to talk to you.
I don't want to, but I've got to.

1305
01:43:10,522 --> 01:43:12,718
The hardest part is talking to you now.

1306
01:43:12,792 --> 01:43:14,760
I don't mind about the rest.

1307
01:43:15,594 --> 01:43:20,157
- It's about Krug and Van Meer.
- You've guessed.

1308
01:43:20,701 --> 01:43:23,602
Not till last night. I've been worried...

1309
01:43:24,205 --> 01:43:25,673
but I believed in you.

1310
01:43:25,740 --> 01:43:27,265
You shouldn't.

1311
01:43:28,710 --> 01:43:32,010
It's true, then, what I wouldn't believe?

1312
01:43:32,316 --> 01:43:35,752
Yes. I'm to be arrested when we land...

1313
01:43:36,721 --> 01:43:39,155
as a spy, shipped back to London.

1314
01:43:39,658 --> 01:43:44,358
It's quite all right, except,
just the one phase of it. You.

1315
01:43:45,264 --> 01:43:47,358
That's why I've got to talk to you.

1316
01:43:49,069 --> 01:43:52,507
I should like for you to see a little
from my point of view...

1317
01:43:53,309 --> 01:43:56,973
it might help you afterwards.

1318
01:43:57,280 --> 01:43:59,874
First about yourself, my deceiving you.

1319
01:44:00,050 --> 01:44:03,145
I didn't want you involved in any part
because you're English...

1320
01:44:03,221 --> 01:44:06,520
half-English anyway. I'm not.
I'm just coated with an English accent.

1321
01:44:06,591 --> 01:44:07,890
A thin coat.

1322
01:44:08,427 --> 01:44:11,886
I fought for my country in my heart
in a very difficult way.

1323
01:44:12,299 --> 01:44:16,702
Sometimes it's harder to fight
dishonorably than nobly in the open.

1324
01:44:17,906 --> 01:44:21,138
I used my country's methods
because I was born with them.

1325
01:44:21,210 --> 01:44:24,236
I don't intend on making this plea
to the court-martial.

1326
01:44:25,014 --> 01:44:28,382
I'm making it only to my daughter
whom I loved dearly...

1327
01:44:29,086 --> 01:44:33,148
and before whom I feel a little ashamed.

1328
01:44:38,430 --> 01:44:41,923
What you say to me now
means more to me than any verdict.

1329
01:44:42,637 --> 01:44:43,934
My dear...

1330
01:44:44,705 --> 01:44:48,437
Steward, this is not for me.
It was a mistake.

1331
01:44:50,346 --> 01:44:53,645
I'm not sitting 14 hours
playing hide-and-seek with her.

1332
01:44:53,716 --> 01:44:55,684
I'm going to talk to her.

1333
01:44:55,753 --> 01:44:58,847
It can't do any harm,
now that he knows we're aboard.

1334
01:44:58,924 --> 01:45:02,952
- Not a word in front of her, understand?
- I wouldn't dream of talking.

1335
01:45:03,296 --> 01:45:06,232
- What will you say to her?
- I don't know. I'm all mixed up.

1336
01:45:06,299 --> 01:45:08,860
I love her, and I'm going to help
hang her father.

1337
01:45:08,936 --> 01:45:11,462
I've got to say something. I'll go crazy.

1338
01:45:12,840 --> 01:45:14,809
Have some brandy. You'll feel better.

1339
01:45:14,876 --> 01:45:17,437
You know it always makes me cry harder.

1340
01:45:19,048 --> 01:45:21,449
- Surprised?
- What are you doing here?

1341
01:45:21,519 --> 01:45:23,645
Having myself a ride.

1342
01:45:24,255 --> 01:45:27,520
Carol, I've got to speak to you alone.
It's very important.

1343
01:45:27,592 --> 01:45:30,460
- Do you mind, Mr. Fisher?
- Ffolliott's with you, isn't he?

1344
01:45:30,530 --> 01:45:32,088
In a way, yes.

1345
01:45:32,532 --> 01:45:34,124
You're both after my father.

1346
01:45:34,200 --> 01:45:36,829
You're having him arrested
when we land, aren't you?

1347
01:45:36,904 --> 01:45:39,806
I don't know what you mean.
I never arrested anyone in my life.

1348
01:45:39,874 --> 01:45:43,173
That's a lie. You've followed him
from the beginning.

1349
01:45:43,245 --> 01:45:46,341
That's why you wanted me
out of the way at the inn...

1350
01:45:46,682 --> 01:45:50,881
pretended you loved me so you could...
It's a lie, that's all.

1351
01:45:50,954 --> 01:45:53,446
Everything you've said to me
have been lies.

1352
01:45:53,524 --> 01:45:56,015
- Quite a reunion, isn't it?
- You, too?

1353
01:45:56,095 --> 01:45:59,327
Please. Have a drink, Scott. I'll be back.

1354
01:45:59,399 --> 01:46:01,765
- Where are you going?
- To stretch my legs.

1355
01:46:01,835 --> 01:46:05,033
I read that wire you received.
It was given to me by mistake.

1356
01:46:05,106 --> 01:46:06,596
That's all right, sir.

1357
01:46:06,674 --> 01:46:09,166
You're not going unless I go with you.

1358
01:46:09,243 --> 01:46:12,407
I know you both think
my father is a traitor and a renegade.

1359
01:46:12,482 --> 01:46:14,382
He isn't. Not to me.

1360
01:46:14,484 --> 01:46:17,181
Thank you.
A minority report, but very welcome.

1361
01:46:17,454 --> 01:46:21,858
Carol, I've got nothing to do with spies.
I'm just a reporter here after a story.

1362
01:46:21,926 --> 01:46:23,757
I'm sorry I ever heard of Van Meer.

1363
01:46:23,828 --> 01:46:27,356
<i>I'd blow up the Globe, cut Powers' throat
rather than harm you.</i>

1364
01:46:31,405 --> 01:46:32,599
What is it?

1365
01:46:35,643 --> 01:46:37,771
They've gone crazy. What are they doing?

1366
01:46:37,846 --> 01:46:39,404
Who are they? What is it?

1367
01:46:40,316 --> 01:46:42,877
Call Bob. Tell him we're being attacked.

1368
01:46:47,993 --> 01:46:51,019
Sorry about this, ffolliott.
It has nothing to do with me.

1369
01:46:52,164 --> 01:46:53,131
We're coming down.

1370
01:46:53,198 --> 01:46:55,223
You're the most cool-headed woman
I've ever seen.

1371
01:46:55,301 --> 01:46:56,461
Make Father wear this.

1372
01:46:56,536 --> 01:46:58,300
Here you are. Put these on.

1373
01:47:01,442 --> 01:47:04,207
Come out, sir.
They're all going nuts in there.

1374
01:47:04,279 --> 01:47:05,941
I'll be out immediately.

1375
01:47:06,015 --> 01:47:08,745
What am I going to say?
This isn't like bad weather.

1376
01:47:08,818 --> 01:47:11,310
Tell them it's a mistake,
that it's target practice.

1377
01:47:12,790 --> 01:47:15,315
I know it's funny for me to ask you
to be calm.

1378
01:47:15,393 --> 01:47:17,258
We're doing the best we can.

1379
01:47:18,764 --> 01:47:19,855
Get back.

1380
01:47:25,439 --> 01:47:27,236
Are we all going to drown?

1381
01:47:28,142 --> 01:47:31,874
Keep away from that window, sir.
It might be dangerous. Sit back.

1382
01:47:32,347 --> 01:47:34,475
I'm not going to put this on.

1383
01:47:34,884 --> 01:47:37,648
I've never heard of anything so stupid.

1384
01:47:37,720 --> 01:47:40,052
I'll see the British Consul as soon as l...

1385
01:47:54,007 --> 01:47:55,373
She's gone.

1386
01:48:01,517 --> 01:48:03,452
What in the name of heaven
are they doing?

1387
01:48:11,128 --> 01:48:13,529
Switch off the gas.
You've got the other board motor.

1388
01:48:13,599 --> 01:48:16,466
- They cut off the other starboard motor.
- Right.

1389
01:48:16,769 --> 01:48:19,864
It's the Germans. They're sorry.
They thought we were a bomber.

1390
01:48:19,939 --> 01:48:21,737
She'll rescue us straight-away.

1391
01:48:21,809 --> 01:48:23,367
The wings are off.

1392
01:48:27,116 --> 01:48:29,584
- Let me get out!
- Come away from that door.

1393
01:48:29,985 --> 01:48:31,919
We can't just stay here.

1394
01:48:31,988 --> 01:48:34,218
When she hits the water,
the tail's the best place.

1395
01:48:34,291 --> 01:48:35,417
Come on.

1396
01:51:08,982 --> 01:51:12,977
No good staying on here,
she's going under. Quick, onto the wing.

1397
01:52:07,522 --> 01:52:09,514
Look, there's the pilot.

1398
01:52:35,623 --> 01:52:39,152
- Don't let him on, you fools!
- Shut your mouth!

1399
01:52:39,229 --> 01:52:40,958
I'm throwing that swine off.

1400
01:52:41,030 --> 01:52:43,829
He's right. It won't hold us.
I'd better slip away.

1401
01:52:43,901 --> 01:52:46,894
I'll move to the other end.
That might make it lighter here.

1402
01:53:07,430 --> 01:53:08,988
He's gone!

1403
01:53:19,412 --> 01:53:22,677
Johnny, don't go! You'll be washed away!

1404
01:53:29,391 --> 01:53:31,086
Johnny, come back!

1405
01:54:04,200 --> 01:54:05,293
Look!

1406
01:54:08,005 --> 01:54:10,406
Must be the enemy coming to pick us up.

1407
01:54:11,576 --> 01:54:12,942
Is it the enemy?

1408
01:54:13,979 --> 01:54:15,572
We're all right. She's American.

1409
01:54:18,505 --> 01:54:21,373
American ship picked us up
and is taking us back to London.

1410
01:54:21,443 --> 01:54:23,876
I can't tell you what happened.

1411
01:54:24,112 --> 01:54:26,946
I'll wire from London in a few days. Bye.

1412
01:54:27,750 --> 01:54:30,412
It's awkward, I just spoke to the captain.

1413
01:54:30,486 --> 01:54:32,682
He insists on acting the true blue neutral.

1414
01:54:32,756 --> 01:54:35,726
"Enemy waters," he says. Not a line
to the press from his ship.

1415
01:54:35,793 --> 01:54:37,351
Can't send out any stories?

1416
01:54:37,428 --> 01:54:39,556
We can use the phone
for private messages.

1417
01:54:39,632 --> 01:54:42,226
<i>"Hello, Aunt Effie,
safe aboard the Mohican.</i>

1418
01:54:42,301 --> 01:54:43,894
"Feeling tiptop."

1419
01:54:44,471 --> 01:54:48,135
Two days before we get to London,
we get scooped on our own story.

1420
01:54:48,209 --> 01:54:51,441
- You have a crack at brass buttons.
- Even if he says okay...

1421
01:54:51,513 --> 01:54:53,641
what good will it do me?
My hands are tied.

1422
01:54:53,715 --> 01:54:55,307
- What are you talking about?
- Carol.

1423
01:54:55,385 --> 01:54:58,549
I came 4,000 miles to get a story.
I get shot at...

1424
01:54:58,622 --> 01:55:02,457
I got pushed off buildings.
I get the story, then I got to shut up.

1425
01:55:03,295 --> 01:55:06,423
I'm sincere. I'm not throwing her father
up for grabs.

1426
01:55:06,498 --> 01:55:09,798
He died like a hero to save her
and the rest of us.

1427
01:55:10,303 --> 01:55:12,101
I'm talking through my hat.

1428
01:55:12,172 --> 01:55:14,470
The whole point is, he was her father.

1429
01:55:14,541 --> 01:55:16,669
I won't play Judas to the only girl...

1430
01:55:16,744 --> 01:55:19,179
I'm very glad you said that.

1431
01:55:19,247 --> 01:55:21,375
- You all dry and everything?
- I'm all right.

1432
01:55:21,450 --> 01:55:23,351
Send the whole story.

1433
01:55:23,420 --> 01:55:25,479
- We'll talk about that later.
- Please.

1434
01:55:25,555 --> 01:55:29,083
You can't help me by protecting my father.

1435
01:55:29,160 --> 01:55:31,025
I'm in love with you.

1436
01:55:31,095 --> 01:55:33,724
I can't hit you with a scandal
for a wedding present.

1437
01:55:34,968 --> 01:55:37,265
My father fought for his country his way.

1438
01:55:37,804 --> 01:55:40,273
It wasrt a straight way,
but it was a hard way.

1439
01:55:40,740 --> 01:55:43,676
And I've got to fight for my country
a hard way.

1440
01:55:44,012 --> 01:55:46,447
Okay, if that's the way you feel.

1441
01:55:48,383 --> 01:55:49,646
That's for me.

1442
01:55:49,719 --> 01:55:52,688
I put in a call to my uncle, Uncle Powers.

1443
01:55:53,090 --> 01:55:54,114
Hello?

1444
01:55:54,926 --> 01:55:57,724
<i>Johnny Jones is calling from the Mohican.</i>

1445
01:55:57,795 --> 01:56:01,596
What's he doing there?
Johnny wouldn't call if it wasrt a story.

1446
01:56:01,667 --> 01:56:05,866
Hold the presses. Send Bradley in here.
Tell him we're breaking up Page 1.

1447
01:56:05,939 --> 01:56:08,840
- Hello.
- Hello, Mr. Powers. This is Johnny Jones.

1448
01:56:08,908 --> 01:56:10,809
Here comes the captain.

1449
01:56:13,247 --> 01:56:16,810
Mr. Powers, keep your ear glued
to this phone and don't hang up.

1450
01:56:22,926 --> 01:56:25,952
- Mr. Haverstock, I want to talk with you.
- Yes, sir.

1451
01:56:26,031 --> 01:56:28,864
- I just found out you're a newspaperman.
- That's right.

1452
01:56:29,901 --> 01:56:32,097
Why didn't you tell me
when I questioned you?

1453
01:56:32,171 --> 01:56:34,572
- You lied to me.
- My dear Captain...

1454
01:56:34,641 --> 01:56:37,702
when you're shot down
in a British plane by a German destroyer...

1455
01:56:37,779 --> 01:56:41,011
300 miles off the coast of England,
Latitude 45...

1456
01:56:41,083 --> 01:56:43,745
have been hanging
on a half-submerged wing for hours...

1457
01:56:43,819 --> 01:56:46,755
waiting to drown
with other stricken human beings...

1458
01:56:46,822 --> 01:56:49,759
you're liable to forget
you're a newspaperman.

1459
01:56:49,827 --> 01:56:53,855
You'll have to forget it
for as long as you're on this ship.

1460
01:56:53,931 --> 01:56:55,991
I can't understand your attitude, sir.

1461
01:56:56,068 --> 01:56:58,902
You performed a heroic rescue,
Captain John Martin.

1462
01:56:58,971 --> 01:57:03,305
- You took us out of the sea.
- You're not sending a thing from this ship.

1463
01:57:03,376 --> 01:57:04,708
You're right, Captain.

1464
01:57:04,778 --> 01:57:07,247
We mustrt embarrass
the United States government.

1465
01:57:07,315 --> 01:57:09,011
Exactly. That's my point.

1466
01:57:10,752 --> 01:57:14,986
That's the story I've got. I won't print it.
I think you ought to hear it first.

1467
01:57:15,058 --> 01:57:16,787
That's only fair, Captain.

1468
01:57:20,531 --> 01:57:22,999
You know who headed that movement
in London?

1469
01:57:23,067 --> 01:57:24,295
Mr. Stephen Fisher.

1470
01:57:24,369 --> 01:57:26,803
The man who ran
the Universal Peace Party?

1471
01:57:26,873 --> 01:57:28,534
- Why, that's preposterous.
- Yes.

1472
01:57:28,608 --> 01:57:31,076
The Mr. Fisher who was drowned
a few hours ago.

1473
01:57:31,144 --> 01:57:34,205
His peace party was a cover-up
for spies and traitors.

1474
01:57:34,281 --> 01:57:37,116
He was going to be arrested and deported.

1475
01:57:37,185 --> 01:57:41,054
- Those are facts.
- I can't believe it. He was a friend of mine.

1476
01:57:41,124 --> 01:57:44,526
He engineered the kidnapping
of Van Meer, the Dutch diplomat.

1477
01:57:44,595 --> 01:57:47,291
- Nobody would believe that.
- It's the truth.

1478
01:57:47,364 --> 01:57:49,595
- I refuse...
- Dear Captain, wait a minute.

1479
01:57:49,667 --> 01:57:53,195
This young lady should know
whether it's the truth or not.

1480
01:57:53,272 --> 01:57:56,333
Yes, I ought to know.
Mr. Fisher was my father.

1481
01:57:56,976 --> 01:57:58,969
And I want the story printed.

1482
01:57:59,679 --> 01:58:02,878
- What's that?
- I guess that's my uncle.

1483
01:58:05,387 --> 01:58:07,514
Hello, Uncle. How are you?

1484
01:58:09,526 --> 01:58:12,758
How's Aunt Sadie? I'm all right, thanks.

1485
01:58:12,830 --> 01:58:15,891
We had a little accident.
I can't tell you about it now.

1486
01:58:15,967 --> 01:58:17,935
I'll write to you.

1487
01:58:18,103 --> 01:58:19,867
I'm going back to Europe.

1488
01:58:20,206 --> 01:58:22,835
I was just wondering
if you had any instructions for me.

1489
01:58:22,909 --> 01:58:26,107
Yes. Keep on the job.
Have you got all that down?

1490
01:58:26,180 --> 01:58:27,670
Rush it out at once.

1491
01:58:40,498 --> 01:58:41,828
This is London.

1492
01:58:41,899 --> 01:58:44,891
We have as a guest tonight
a soldier of the press...

1493
01:58:44,969 --> 01:58:46,870
one of the army of historians...

1494
01:58:46,939 --> 01:58:49,670
writing history from beside
the cannors mouth...

1495
01:58:49,975 --> 01:58:52,467
<i>Foreign correspondent
of the New York Globe...</i>

1496
01:58:52,546 --> 01:58:53,774
Huntley Haverstock.

1497
01:58:53,848 --> 01:58:55,180
Hello, America.

1498
01:58:55,250 --> 01:58:58,048
I've been watching a part of the world
being blown to pieces.

1499
01:58:58,119 --> 01:59:00,849
A part of the world
as nice as Vermont, Ohio...

1500
01:59:00,922 --> 01:59:03,118
Virginia, and California, and Illinois...

1501
01:59:03,192 --> 01:59:06,185
lies ripped up and bleeding
like a steer in a slaughterhouse.

1502
01:59:06,263 --> 01:59:10,461
I've seen things that make the history of
savages read like Pollyanna legends.

1503
01:59:11,035 --> 01:59:14,403
- We'll have to postpone the broadcast.
- Let's go on as long as we can.

1504
01:59:14,473 --> 01:59:16,566
Madam, we have a shelter downstairs.

1505
01:59:17,243 --> 01:59:20,510
- How about it, Carol?
- They're listening in America, Johnny.

1506
01:59:20,581 --> 01:59:22,775
Okay. We'll tell them, then.

1507
01:59:23,985 --> 01:59:26,887
I can't read the rest of my speech
because the lights went out...

1508
01:59:26,955 --> 01:59:28,923
so I'll have to talk off the cuff.

1509
01:59:29,325 --> 01:59:32,658
That noise you hear isn't static.
It's death coming to London.

1510
01:59:32,729 --> 01:59:36,257
You can hear the bombs
falling on the streets and the homes.

1511
01:59:36,333 --> 01:59:40,168
Don't tune me out. Hang on.
This is a big story. You're part of it.

1512
01:59:40,238 --> 01:59:43,902
It's too late to do anything here
except stand in the dark, let them come.

1513
01:59:43,976 --> 01:59:47,606
It's as if the lights were out everywhere
except in America.

1514
01:59:48,082 --> 01:59:49,811
Keep those lights burning.

1515
01:59:49,884 --> 01:59:52,444
Cover them with steel,
ring them with guns...

1516
01:59:52,520 --> 01:59:55,513
build a canopy of battleships
and bombing planes around them.

1517
01:59:55,591 --> 01:59:57,991
Hello, America, hang onto your lights.

1518
01:59:58,060 --> 02:00:00,393
They're the only lights left in the world.
